{"title_page": "Enemy of the World", "text_new": "#redirect [[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Sunday]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Doctor Who serial|The Enemy of the World}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Enemy of the World\n| type       = [[Studio Album]]\n| artist     = [[Four Year Strong]]\n| cover      = Four Year Strong - Enemy of the World.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = March 9, 2010\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Pop punk]],<ref name=AllMusic/> [[melodic hardcore]]\n| length     = 38:13\n| label      = [[DCD2 Records|Decaydance]], [[Universal Motown Records|Universal Motown]]\n| producer   = [[Machine (producer)|Machine]]\n| prev_title = [[Explains It All]]\n| prev_year  = 2009\n| next_title = [[In Some Way, Shape, or Form]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Enemy of the World\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = It Must Really Suck to Be Four Year Strong Right Now\n | single1date = December 21, 2009\n | single2     = Wasting Time (Eternal Summer)\n | single2date = February 9, 2010\n | single3     = What the Hell Is a Gigawatt?\n | single3date = February 27, 2010\n | single4     = Tonight We Feel Alive (On a Saturday)\n | single4date = May 11, 2010\n}}\n}}\n'''''Enemy of the World''''' is the fourth [[studio album]] by American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Four Year Strong]]. It is the final album to feature keyboardist Josh Lyford prior to his departure from the band in April 2011.\n\n==Release==\n\"It Must Really Suck to Be Four Year Strong Right Now\" is the album's first single, released in the iTunes Store on December 21, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1482032 |title=New Four Year Strong Single on iTunes - News Article |publisher=AbsolutePunk.net |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref> \"Wasting Time (Eternal Summer)\" became available for streaming on AbsolutePunk on February 11. It was announced be the album's second single,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theaquarian.com/2010/02/11/interview-with-dan-o%E2%80%99connor-and-josh-lyford-of-four-year-strong-it-definitely-doesnt-suck-to-be-four-year-strong-right-now/ |title=Interview with Dan O\u2019Connor and Josh Lyford of Four Year Strong: It Definitely Doesn\u2019t Suck To Be Four Year Strong Right Now &#124; The Aquarian Weekly |publisher=Theaquarian.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref> and was released on February 9, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/wasting-time-eternal-summer/id353242043?i=353242154 |title=iTunes Store |publisher=itunes.apple.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref> \"What the Hell Is a Gigawatt?\" was made available for streaming on [[Purevolume]] on February 27, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1574802 |title=What The Hell Is A Gigawatt? - News Article |publisher=AbsolutePunk.net |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Four Year Strong announced what they named \"the platinum of pre-orders\", a list of novelty packages involving the purchasing of the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.killyourstereo.com/news/5841/four-year-strong-launch-awesome-preorders/ |title=Four Year Strong launch awesome preorders &#124; News |publisher=Kill Your Stereo |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref> In February and March, the band performed at [[Soundwave (Australian music festival)|Soundwave festival]] in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.kerrang.com:80/2009/10/my_chem_you_me_at_six_paramore.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091016054920/http://www2.kerrang.com/2009/10/my_chem_you_me_at_six_paramore.html|title=My Chem, You Me At Six, Paramore, and Gallows for Soundwave|work=Kerrang!|author=Dan|date=October 13, 2009|archivedate=October 16, 2009|accessdate=June 4, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> The vinyl edition of the album was made available to pre-order on March 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1577212 |title=Vinyl Year Strong - News Article |publisher=AbsolutePunk.net |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref> It was released through [[DCD2 Records|Decaydance]] and [[Universal Motown Records]] on March 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1468921 |title=FYS Is An Enemy of the World - News Article |publisher=AbsolutePunk.net |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=MusicRemedy.com / |url=http://musicremedy.com/f/four-year-strong/album/enemy-of-the-world-7972.html |title=Four Year Strong release Enemy Of The World album |publisher=Musicremedy.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref> In March and April, the band went on a US tour alongside [[Every Time I Die]], [[Polar Bear Club]] and [[Trapped Under Ice]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.punknews.org/article/36801/tours-every-time-i-die-four-year-strong-polar-bear-club-trapped-under-ice|title=Every Time I Die / Four Year Strong / Polar Bear Club / Trapped Under Ice|work=Punknews.org|publisher=Aubin Paul|author=Paul, Aubin|date=January 25, 2010|accessdate=July 11, 2017}}</ref> \"Tonight We Feel Alive (On a Saturday)\" was released to radio on May 11.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allaccess.com/mail/archive/eweekly/alternative/2010-5-4.html|title=AllAccess.com Alternative eWeekly|work=AllAccess|date=May 4, 2010|accessdate=July 2, 2016}}</ref> The group performed on the [[Kerrang! Tour]] in the UK in February 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deadpress.co.uk/news-the-wonder-years-are-added-onto-relentless-kerrang-tour-2011/|title=NEWS: The Wonder Years are added onto Relentless Kerrang! Tour 2011!|work=Dead Press!|author=Redrup, Zach|date=October 13, 2010|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AbsolutePunk]]\n| rev1Score = (87%)<ref name=\"drewreview\"/>\n| rev2 = All Metal Music\n| rev2score = {{Rating|9|10}}<ref name=AllMusic>[http://www.allmetalmusic.co.uk/#/four-year-strong/4544355664 ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112085630/http://www.allmetalmusic.co.uk/ |date=2010-11-12 }}</ref>\n| rev3 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1725658|pure_url=yes}}|title=''Enemy of the World''|author= |publisher=[[Allmusic]] |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Idobi Radio|idobi]]\n| rev4score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|author=Popaganda |url=http://idobi.com/news/2010/03/album-review-four-year-strong-takes-over-the-world-with-heavy-riffs/ |title=Album review: Four Year Strong takes over the world with heavy riffs |publisher=idobi |date=2010-03-09 |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Kerrang!]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kerrang.com/blog/2010/06/kerrang_magazine_02062010.html |title=Kerrang! Kerrang! Magazine 02/06/2010 |publisher=Kerrang.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n| rev8 = Punknews.org\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}} <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.punknews.org/review/9296/four-year-strong-enemy-of-the-world|title=Four Year Strong - Enemy Of The World |publisher=Punknews.org|date= |accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| rev9 = Review Rinse Repeat\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|4.5|5}} <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewrinserepeat.com/artist/four-year-strong/album/enemy-of-the-world/review |title=Four Year Strong - Enemy Of The World |publisher=Review Rinse Repeat |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n| rev10 = [[Sputnikmusic]]\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|4|5}} <ref>[http://sputnikmusic.com/review/37077/Four-Year-Strong-Enemy-of-the-World/ Four Year Strong Enemy of the World] - Sputnik Music</ref>\n}}\nAbsolutePunk reviewer Drew Beringer was extremely positive in his review, saying ''Enemy of the World'' \"is a pop-punk juggernaut\" and tops their previous album ''[[Rise or Die Trying]]'' by far.<ref name=\"drewreview\">{{cite web|url=http://absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=1570842 |title=Four Year Strong - Enemy Of The World - Album Review |publisher=AbsolutePunk.net |date=2010-03-09 |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n\nThe album sold over 12,000 copies in its first week, debuting at number 47 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{Cite news |url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=four year strong|chart=all}}|title=Enemy of the World - Four Year Strong|author= |work=Billboard.com |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=September 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"Wasting Time (Eternal Summer)\" was nominated at the [[Kerrang! Awards]] for Best Single, but lost to \"[[Liquid Confidence (Nothing to Lose)|Liquid Confidence]]\" by [[You Me at Six]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kerrang.com:80/blog/2010/07/and_the_winners_are_1.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125025129/http://www.kerrang.com/blog/2010/07/and_the_winners_are_1.html|title=And the winners are...|work=Kerrang!|publisher=Bauer Media Group|author=Dan|date=July 29, 2010|archivedate=November 25, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The album was included at number 39 on ''Rock Sound''{{'}}s \"The 51 Most Essential Pop Punk Albums of All Time\" list.<ref>Bird, ed. 2014, p. 70</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written by Dan O'Connor and Alan Day, except where noted.\n{{tracklist\n| title1          = It Must Really Suck to Be Four Year Strong Right Now\n| note1           = O'Connor\n| length1         = 3:16\n| title2          = Tonight We Feel Alive (On a Saturday)\n| length2         = 3:43\n| title3          = Wasting Time (Eternal Summer)\n| note3           = O'Connor\n| length3         = 3:18\n| title4          = Nineteen with Neck Tatz\n| length4         = 3:24\n| title5          = Find My Way Back\n| length5         = 3:28\n| title6          = What the Hell Is a Gigawatt?\n| note6           = featuring Jay Pepito of Reign Supreme\n| length6         = 3:07\n| title7          = One Step at a Time\n| length7         = 3:06\n| title8          = This Body Pays the Bill$\n| length8         = 3:20\n| title9          = Paul Revere's Midnight Ride\n| length9         = 3:55\n| title10         = Flannel Is the Color of My Energy\n| length10        = 3:29\n| title11         = Enemy of the World\n| length11        = 4:02\n|total_length = 38:13\n}}\n\n;Bonus tracks\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = iTune bonus track\n| collapsed       = yes\n| title12         = Listen, Do You Smell Something?\n| length12        = 3:37\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Special edition bonus tracks\n| collapsed       = yes\n| title12         = Bad News Bearz\n| length12        = 3:15\n| title13         = Tonight We Feel Alive (On a Saturday)\n| note13          = acoustic\n| length13        = 4:41\n| title14         = One Step at a Time\n| note14          = acoustic\n| length14        = 3:27\n| title15         = Find My Way Back\n| note15          = acoustic\n| length15        = 3:31\n| title16         = Wasting Time (Eternal Summer)\n| note16          = acoustic\n| length16        = 3:20\n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = It's Not the Size of the 7-inch... It's How You Use It (EP)\n| collapsed       = yes\n| title1          = It Must Really Suck to Be Four Year Strong Right Now\n| length1         = 3:16\n| title2          = Cavalier\n| length2         = 3:07\n}}\n\n==Song titles==\n*\"It Must Really Suck to Be Four Year Strong Right Now\" comes from a comment made by Scott Heisel of ''Alternative Press'' in a review of the [[Set Your Goals (band)|Set Your Goals]] album ''[[This Will Be the Death of Us]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/reviews/entry/thiswillbethedeathofus/ |title=Alternative Press &#124; Reviews &#124; Set Your Goals - This Will Be The Death Of Us |publisher=Altpress.com |date=2009-07-21 |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n*\"What the Hell Is a Gigawatt?\" is a line from the film ''[[Back to the Future]]''.\n*\"Flannel Is the Color of My Energy\" is a reference to the chorus of the [[311 (band)|311]] song \"[[Amber (song)|Amber]]\".\n*The title of the bonus track \"Listen, Do You Smell Something?\" is a line in the film ''[[Ghostbusters]]''.\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart\n! Peak<br/>position\n|-\n| U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=four year strong|chart=Billboard 200}} |title=Four Year Strong Music News & Info |publisher=Billboard.com |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Albums]]<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Rock Albums]]<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|9\n|-\n| U.S. ''Billboard'' [[Digital Albums]]<ref name=\"billboard\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|}\n\n==Personnel==\n<!--Four Year Strong does NOT have pre-determined lead and rhythm guitarists nor a lead vocalist. Everything is a 50/50 split between Alan and Dan, please stop giving misleading information.-->\n*Alan Day \u2013 [[lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar|rhythm]] and [[lead guitar]] \n*Dan O'Connor \u2013 [[lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar|rhythm]] and [[lead guitar]]\n*Joe Weiss \u2013 [[bass guitar]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n*Jake Massucco \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n*Josh Lyford \u2013 [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[synthesizer]], [[Screaming (music)|unclean vocals]]\n\n;Additional personnel\n* Jay Pepito (of Reign Supreme) \u2013 additional vocals  on \"What the Hell Is a Gigawatt?\"\n\n;Production\n* Machine \u2013 producer\n* [[John Feldmann]] \u2013 mixing\n* Bradon Paddock & Erik Ron \u2013 mix assistants\n* Joe Gastwirt \u2013 mastering\n* [[Will Putney]], Machine \u2013 engineer\n* Clinton Bradley \u2013 additional synth programming\n* Jeremy Comitas, Bill Purcell \u2013 editing/Pro Tools\n*  [[Pete Wentz]] \u2013 A&R for [[DCD2 Records|Decaydance Records]]\n* Shep Goodman \u2013 A&R for [[Universal Motown]]\n* Elizabeth Vago \u2013 A&R coordination\n* Cliff Rigano \u2013 product manager\n* Ken Kelly \u2013 illustrations\n* Joe Spix \u2013 art direction & design\n\n==References==\n; Citations\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n;Sources\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal|editor1-last=Bird|editor1-first=Ryan|title=The 51 Most Essential Pop Punk Albums of All Time|journal=Rock Sound|date=September 2014|issue=191|publisher=Freeway Press Inc.|location=London|issn=1465-0185}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n<!-- This is a licensed stream for the album, which is allowed under Wikipedia polices -->\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL5xmKPoiUnF_e3ciLqsnm77LhcO9qn4Ky ''Enemy of the World''] at [[YouTube]] (streamed copy where licensed)\n\n{{Four Year Strong}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Enemy Of The World}}\n[[Category:2010 albums]]\n[[Category:Four Year Strong albums]]\n[[Category:Albums with cover art by Ken Kelly (artist)]]\n[[Category:Decaydance Records albums]]\n[[Category:Universal Motown Records albums]]\n", "name_user": "2604:5040:10:9987::1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 949940595 bySerols(talk) Justin Knapp > Weekly Shonen Sunday)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enemy_of_the_World"}
{"title_page": "Mellanox Technologies", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Mellanox Technologies Ltd.\n| logo = Mellanox Technologies logo.svg\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{NASDAQ|MLNX}}\n| founded = {{start date and age|1999}} in [[Yokneam Illit]], [[Israel]]\n| founders = Eyal Waldman, Shai Cohen, Roni Ashuri, Michael Kagan, Evelyn Landman, Shimon Rottenberg, Eitan Zahavi, Udi Katz, Alon Webman\n| location = [[Sunnyvale, California|Sunnyvale]], [[California]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mellanox.com/content/pages.php?pg=contact |title=Mellanox office locations |publisher= Mellanox Technologies}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.linkedin.com/company/mellanox-technologies |title=Mellanox Technologies |publisher= Linkedin Corporation}}</ref>\n| key_people = Eyal Waldman, <small>CEO</small>\n| num_employees = 2900 (March 2017)\n| revenue = {{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]863,9 Million <small>(''FY17'')</small>\n{{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]658,1 Million <small>(''FY15'')</small><ref name = CorpFact2>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/financialpost/20160127006351/en/Mellanox-Achieves-Record-Quarterly-Annual-Revenue |title=Mellanox Achieves Record Quarterly and Annual Revenue |publisher=Mellanox Technologies |year=2016 |accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref>\n{{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]463.6 Million <small>(''FY14'')</small><ref name = CorpFact3>{{cite web|url=http://www.mellanox.com/related-docs/company/MLNX_Corporate_Deck.pdf |title=Corporate Overview |publisher=Mellanox Technologies |year=2015 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]118.31 Million <small>(''FY12'')</small>\n| net_income = {{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]111.38 Million <small>(''FY12'')</small>\n| parent = \n| industry = Communication equipment\n| products = [[Ethernet]] and [[InfiniBand]] [[switches]] <br> [[host bus adapter]]s\n| homepage = {{URL|www.mellanox.com}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:MELLANOX - 1024.jpg|thumb|Mellanox Headquarters in [[Yokneam Illit]]]]\n'''Mellanox Technologies Ltd.''' ({{lang-he|\u05de\u05dc\u05d0\u05e0\u05d5\u05e7\u05e1 \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05e2\"\u05de}}) is an [[Israel]]i-American multinational supplier of computer networking products based on [[InfiniBand]] and [[Ethernet]] technology. Mellanox offers adapters, switches, software, cables and silicon for markets including [[High Performance Computing|high-performance computing]], [[data center]]s, [[cloud computing]], [[computer data storage]] and financial services.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nOn March 11, 2019, [[Nvidia]] announced its intent to acquire the company for $6.9 billion.<ref>https://www.engadget.com/2019/03/11/nvidia-acquisition-mellanox/</ref><ref>https://nvidianews.nvidia.com/news/nvidia-to-acquire-mellanox-for-6-9-billion</ref> Other companies willing to acquire Mellanox were [[Intel]], [[Xilinx]] and [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/03/11/daily-crunch-nvidia-mellanox/|title=Daily Crunch: NVIDIA is buying Mellanox for $6.9B|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n===1999\u20132009===\nMellanox was founded in 1999 by former [[Israelis|Israeli]] executives of Intel Corporation and Galileo Technology (which was acquired by [[Marvell Technology Group]] in October 2000 for $2.8 billion<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4113479/Marvell-to-acquire-LAN-chip-supplier-Galileo-for-2-7-billion-in-stock |title= Marvell to acquire LAN-chip supplier Galileo for $2.7 billion in stock |publisher= eetimes.com |date= 2000-10-17 |accessdate= 2011-06-12 }}</ref>) Eyal Waldman, Shai Cohen, Roni Ashuri, Michael Kagan, Evelyn Landman, Eitan Zahavi, Shimon Rottenberg, Udi Katz and Alon Webman.<ref name=\"CorpFact3\" /> Eyal Waldman founded Mellanox in the Israel city of [[Yokneam Illit|Yokne'am]].<ref name=times-ceo>{{cite news |last=Solomon |first=Shoshanna |date=December 26, 2017 |title=When a startup gets big, the environment gets rougher, says Mellanox CEO |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/for-monday-once-you-become-big-the-environment-can-turn-hostile-mellanox-ceo-for-monday/ | work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Initially founded as an [[integrated circuit]] (chip) manufacturer, it evolved into a producer of complete end-to-end systems by 2009.<ref name=bbg/>  The company raised over $89 million in 3 financing rounds of [[venture capital]].{{When|date=April 2017}}<ref name=globes>{{cite web |url= http://www.globes.co.il/serveen/globes/docview.asp?did=1000685576&fid=1725 |title=Oracle acquires $11m more Mellanox shares |first= Tali |last=Tsipori |publisher= [[Globes]] |date= September 25, 2011 |accessdate= 2011-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.crn.com/news/channel-programs/18827937/vc-money-continues-to-drain-into-infiniband-mellanox-secures-56m.htm;jsessionid=p3jwDPOPqFQFywCdlyPgUQ**.ecappj01 |title= VC Money Continues To Drain Into InfiniBand: Mellanox Secures $56M |first= Joseph F. |last= Kovar |publisher=[[CRN Magazine|CRN]] |date= February 11, 2002 |accessdate= 2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nThe company went public in 2007, with an [[initial public offering]] on [[NASDAQ]] that raised $102 million, and valued the company at over half a billion dollars.<ref name=eet1>{{cite news |url= http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4186774/Mellanox-raises-102-million-with-IPO-on-Nasdaq |title= Mellanox raises $102 million with IPO on Nasdaq |first=John |last= Walko |work= [[EE Times]] |date= February 8, 2007 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> Created in 2009, Mellanox's investment fund was publicly launched in 2014.<ref name=globes-a/>\n\n===2010\u2013present===\nIn 2010, [[Oracle Corporation]] became a major investor in the company, holding around 10% of its stock.<ref name=globes/> Oracle uses InfiniBand technology in its [[Exadata]] and Exalogic appliances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/77108/20101029/oracle-mellanox-hp-dell-ibm-switch-chip-infiniband-siwtches-solaris-sun-acquired.htm |title=Oracle buys 10 pct stake in Mellanox, will Dell, HP, IBM follow suit? |first=Carl |last=Bagh |publisher=[[International Business Times]] |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112045944/http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/77108/20101029/oracle-mellanox-hp-dell-ibm-switch-chip-infiniband-siwtches-solaris-sun-acquired.htm |archivedate=November 12, 2010 }}</ref> Stock shares were also listed on the [[Tel Aviv Stock Exchange]], until 2013 when the company de-listed itself, but remained on NASDAQ.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Mellanox Technologies Initiates Process to Delist Ordinary Shares from Tel Aviv Stock Exchange |date= May 30, 2013 |work= Press release |url= http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=1032 |access-date= April 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, Mellanox acquired Voltaire Ltd., a provider of data center switches for about $218 million.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=527 |title= Mellanox Technologies, Ltd. Completes Acquisition of Voltaire, Ltd. |work= Press release |date=February 7, 2011 |access-date= April 23, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"reg2010\" />\n\nIn 2016, Mellanox Technologies began to employ programmers in the [[Gaza Strip]], in addition to its team of [[Israeli Arab]] programmers and programmers in Ramallah and Nablus.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/business/1.725521 Mellanox Hires Programmers in the Gaza Strip]</ref> In 2016, Mellanox had revenues of $857 million.<ref name=times-ceo/> In December 2017, Mellanox announced it would start a new startup accelerator.<ref name=globes-a>{{cite news |last=Habib-Valdhorn |first=Shiri |date= |title=Mellanox to launch startup accelerator |url=http://www.globes.co.il/en/article-mellanox-to-launch-startup-accelerator-1001217054 | work=[[Globes]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Over 2017, shares in the company rose by 55 percent. That year, the company also made its largest acquisition with [[EZchip]].<ref name=times-ceo/>\n\nIn 2019 Mellanox was acquired for $ 6.9 billion by [[Nvidia|Nvidia Corporation]] and it is a definite contender for the largest [[Mergers and acquisitions|M&A]] deal in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/mellanox-technologies-nvidia-to-buy-in-69-billion-deal-2019-3-1028018625|title=Nvidia is buying Mellanox Technologies in a $6.9 billion deal (NVDA) {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\n===Boardroom in 2018===\nThe activist investor [[Starboard Value|Starboard Value LP]] purchased a 10.7% stake in the company in November 2017.<ref name=wsj-starboard/> After acquiring 10.7%, Starboard wrote a letter to the company stating that Starboard attributed the company's \"underperformance compared to other semiconductor companies\" to \"a pattern of weak execution that has included both excessive spending and missed growth opportunities\". The letter called for \"substantial change\".<ref name=toi-solomon>{{cite news |last=Solomon |first=Shoshanna |date=January 8, 2018 |title=Activist investor Starboard calls for \u2018substantial change\u2019 at Israel\u2019s Mellanox |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/activist-investor-starboard-calls-for-substantial-change-at-israels-mellanox/ | work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=reuters-aishwarya>{{cite news |last=Venugopal |first=Aishwarya |date=January 8, 2018 |title=Starboard says chipmaker Mellanox's 2018 targets insufficient |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-starboard-mellanox/starboard-says-chipmaker-mellanoxs-2018-targets-insufficient-idUSKBN1EX0YK | work=[[Reuters]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> The day after, on January 9, 2018,<ref name=ti-cut/> Mellanox announced it would immediately discontinue its 1550&nbsp;nm silicon photonics development activities, with president and CEO Eyal Waldman saying the review of the silicon photonics business had started in May 2017.<ref name=optics-org>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=January 10, 2018 |title=Mellanox to cease 1550nm silicon photonics development |url=http://optics.org/news/9/1/6 | work=optics.org |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Mellanox also said it would fire 100 people, all in the US. At the time, the company employed 2,900 people, mostly in Israel.<ref name=ti-cut>{{cite news |last=Solomon |first=Shoshanna |date=January 10, 2018 |title=Mellanox to cut 100 US jobs as chip line development halted |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/mellanox-to-cut-100-us-jobs-as-chip-line-development-halted/ | work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a \"board battle,\"<ref name=cnbc-stock>{{cite news |last=Schacknow |first=Peter |date=January 18, 2018 |title=Stocks making the biggest moves premarket: MS, WMT, WWW, LQ, AAPL, AA & more |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/18/stocks-making-the-biggest-moves-premarket-ms-wmt-www-lq-aapl-aa-more.html | work=[[CNBC]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> in January 2018, Starboard sent a letter to shareholders asking them to entirely replace the board of directors.<ref name=barrons>{{cite news |last=Ray |first=Tiernan |date=January 18, 2018 |title=Mellanox, Under Siege From Starboard, Surges 6% on Q4 Beat, Outlook |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/mellanox-under-siege-from-starboard-surges-6-on-q4-beat-outlook-1516314219?tesla=y | work=[[Barron's (newspaper)|Barron's]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> On January 17, 2018, it was announced that Starboard was aiming to remove the entire board at Mellanox Technologies. At the time, Mellanox had a $3.3 billion market value.<ref name=wsj-starboard>{{cite news |last=Benoit |first=David |date=January 17, 2018 |title=Starboard Value to Launch Proxy Fight for Entire Board at Mellanox |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/starboard-value-to-launch-proxy-fight-for-entire-board-at-mellanox-1516225802 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |location=New York City, New York |access-date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> Starboard said it would nominate nine candidates for election to the company's board, including Starboard head Jeffrey Smith.<ref name=retuers-nine>{{Citation |last= |first= |date=January 17, 2018 |title=Starboard to nominate nine candidates to Mellanox board |publisher=[[Reuters]] |publication-place= |page= |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mellanox-starboard/starboard-to-nominate-nine-candidates-to-mellanox-board-idUSKBN1F702E |accessdate= January 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisitions ===\n\nIn 2013 Mellanox acquired certain [[assets]] of [[XLoom Communications|XLoom Communications Ltd.]], including opto-electric chip-scale packaging, as well as hired XLoom's technology personnel.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} In July 2013, Mellanox acquired privately held [[Kotura|Kotura, Inc.]], a developer of [[silicon photonics]] optical interconnect technology for high-speed networking.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=1096 | title= Mellanox Technologies, Ltd. Completes Acquisition of Kotura, Inc. | publisher=NASDAQ |accessdate=Aug 15, 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, Mellanox acquired privately held [[IPtronics]] A/S, a designer of optical interconnect components for digital communications.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=1052 | title= Mellanox Technologies, Ltd. Completes Acquisition of IPtronics A/S  | publisher=NASDAQ |accessdate=Jul 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Mellanox acquired privately held [[Integrity Project]], for its software connectivity, low-level development, real-time applications and security technology.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=1321 | title= Mellanox Technologies Ltd. Announces Definitive Agreement to Acquire Integrity Project | publisher=NASDAQ |accessdate=June 24, 2014}}</ref> In February 2016, Mellanox acquired publicly held [[EZchip Semiconductor]], a provider of [[network processor]]s and multi-core processors from EZchip's earlier acquisition of [[Tilera]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n== Manufacturing ==\nMellanox is a [[fabless semiconductor company]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/10003192/web-chip-fabless-mellanox-poised-to-raise-50m-at-company-value-of-250m.html |title=Web-chip fabless Mellanox poised to raise $50m at company value of $250m |publisher=[[TheMarker]] |date=October 30, 2001 |accessdate=2011-10-29 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The current generation of its chips are produced by [[TSMC|Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Corp]].<ref name=\"switchx\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/04/26/mellanox_switchx_switch_chip/|title=Mellanox uncloaks SwitchX network switch-hitter|last=Morgan|first=Timothy Prickett|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-29|publisher=The Register}}</ref>\n\n== Products and market ==\n[[File:MellanoxSC18.jpg|thumb|Mellanox at SC18]]\nMellanox Technologies provides Ethernet and InfiniBand [[Network interface controller|network adapters]], [[Network switch|switches]] and cables for servers and storage used in cloud and enterprise [[data centers]]<ref name=tmc>{{cite web|url=http://10-gigabit-ethernet.tmcnet.com/topics/10-gigabit-ethernet/articles/226214-the-road-with-mellanox-technologies.htm |title=On the Road with Mellanox Technologies |last=Amodio |first=Michelle |publisher=TMCnet |date=October 6, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> based on internally developed [[integrated circuit]]s.<ref name=\"reg2010\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/11/29/mellanox_acquires_voltaire/ |title= Mellanox gobbles up Voltaire for $218m |author= Timothy Prickett Morgan |work= [[The Register]] |date= November 29, 2010 |access-date= April 23, 2017}}</ref> Mellanox offers interconnect products: adapters, switches, cables, software and silicon for a range of markets including high-performance computing, enterprise data centers, [[Web 2.0]], cloud, storage and financial services.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn 2010, a press release from [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] described Mellanox as \"the premier [[switched fabric]] provider for enterprise data centers and [[high performance computing]]\". According to the same press release, Mellanox's InfiniBand technology is faster, more scalable and provides higher throughput than alternative communications technologies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oracle.com/us/corporate/press/183506 |title=Oracle Corporation Makes Strategic Investment In Mellanox Technologies, Ltd. |publisher=[[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] |date=October 27, 2010 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n[[Larry Ellison]], CEO of Oracle, promoted Mellanox's InfiniBand technology.<ref name=bbg>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-04/mellanox-ceo-waldman-sees-revenue-growing-10-fold-after-voltaire-purchase.html |title=Mellanox CEO Sees Sales Rising 10-Fold With Voltaire |first=Gwen |last=Ackerman |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=January 5, 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nMellanox network adapter and switch ASICs support [[Remote direct memory access|RDMA]]/[[RDMA over Converged Ethernet|RoCE]] technology, which are the basis of card and system level products:\n\n*The ConnectX product family of multi-protocol [[Application-specific integrated circuit|ASIC]]<nowiki/>s and adapters supports virtual protocol interconnect, enabling support for both Ethernet and InfiniBand traffic at speeds up to 200Gbit/s. The latest ConnectX-6, and ConnectX-6 Dx adapters have enhanced capabilities such as high speed (up to 200Gb per second), OVS acceleration, Multi-Host support, and inline crypto acceleration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/products_dyn?product_family=268&mtag=connectx_6_en_ic|title=ConnectX-6 Product Family|last=|first=|date=|website=Mellanox|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/products_dyn?product_family=302&mtag=connectx_6_dx_ic|title=ConnectX-6 VPI|last=|first=|date=|website=community.mellanox.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/products_dyn?product_family=302&mtag=connectx_6_dx_ic|title=ConnectX-6 Dx|last=|first=|date=|website=www.mellanox.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> \n*The ConnectX architecture has been described as \"novel\", with excellent performance that is \"very well suited for modern [[multi-core]] platforms\".<ref>{{cite journal|citeseerx = 10.1.1.81.4890 |title=Performance Analysis and Evaluation of Mellanox ConnectX InfiniBand Architecture with Multi-Core Platforms |first1=Sayantan |last1=Sur |first2=Matthew J. |last2=Koop |last3=Lei |first4=Dhabaleswar K. |last4=Panda |journal=hoti |pages=125\u2013134 |publisher=15th Annual IEEE Symposium on High-Performance Interconnects (HOTI 2007) |year=2007}}</ref> The Quantum family of InfiniBand switches supports up to 40 ports running at HDR 200Gbit/s. The Quantum switches offer un-matched latency and packet forwarding performance and support advanced HPC offloads including SHARP (collective operation acceleration) and SHIELD (self-healing) technologies.\n*The Spectrum product family of Ethernet switches.\n*The LinkX product family of cables and transceivers. These products are available in both Ethernet and InfiniBand protocols and SFP, QSFP, OSFP, and DDSFP form factors.\n\n=== High-performance computing ===\nMellanox Technologies' InfiniBand products for [[computer cluster]]s are claimed to be widely deployed in many of the [[TOP500]] list of [[High-performance computing|high-performance computers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=2227|title=Mellanox 200G HDR InfiniBand Accelerates 31% of New InfiniBand Systems on November\u2019s TOP500|last=|first=|date=June 27, 2011|newspaper=Bloomberg|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n=== Storage ===\nMellanox also promotes its products for [[storage area network]]s, and pioneered Ethernet Storage Fabrics (ESF) to replace legacy Fibre Channel SANs (storage area networks).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nextplatform.com/2017/09/26/ascendancy-ethernet-storage-fabrics/|title=The Ascendancy Of Ethernet Storage Fabrics|last=Morgan|first=Timothy Prickett|date=2017-09-26|website=The Next Platform|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Global Operations ===\nIn addition to its global headquarters in the US, Mellanox has offices in Israel, Denmark, China, Russia, Singapore, Taiwan, Japan and the United Kingdom. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/contact?ssn=oaavq86vjgi5sojt4o1dbd9ph7|title=Mellanox Contact Us|website=www.mellanox.com|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Customers ==\n{{As of|2019||df=}} Mellanox had two customers, [[Hewlett-Packard]] and Dell-EMC, both of whom contributed more than 10% of the companies revenues.<ref>https://ir.mellanox.com/node/21816/html</ref>\n\n== Hiring practices ==\nMellanox outsourced some of its engineering to the [[West Bank]]. Rather than setting up offshore engineering centers in the Far East or Eastern Europe, Mellanox hired Palestinian engineers from [[Ramallah]] through a Palestinian outsourcing firm.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/themarker/high-tech-company-aims-to-be-first-israeli-firm-to-hire-palestinian-engineers-1.323311 |title=High-tech company aims to be first Israeli firm to hire Palestinian engineers |first=Tali |last=Heruti-Sover |publisher=[[Haaretz]] |date=November 7, 2010 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> In 2018, Waldman told a Tel Aviv conference hosted by [[Globes]] magazine that over 100 Palestinians are working on Mellanox projects.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://services.globes.co.il/en/article-mellanox-ceo-we-employ-over-100-palestinians-1001242534|title=Mellanox CEO: We employ over 100 Palestinians|last=Levy|first=Aviv|date=21 June 2018|work=Globes|access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nWaldman had previously talked about Mellanox's plans to  build a research and development center in Ramallah, even though it is more expensive than outsourcing to Eastern Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2011/0422/Tech-diplomacy-Israeli-CEO-hires-Palestinian-programmers |title=Tech diplomacy: Israeli CEO hires Palestinian programmers |first=Joshua |last=Mitnick |publisher=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |date=April 22, 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* In November 2012,  Mellanox was named one of the Fastest Growing Companies in Deloitte's 2012 Technology Fast 500 Rankings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mellanox Technologies Ranked Number 364 Fastest Growing Company in North America on Deloitte\u2019s 2012 Technology Fast 500\u2122|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=903|publisher=Mellanox|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n* In November 2012, Mellanox was awarded - 'Readers\u2019 Choice: Best HPC Interconnect Product or Technology' from HPCwire<ref name=HPCwire2012>{{cite web|title=Mellanox Wins Five HPCwire 2012 Readers' and Editors\u2019 Choice Awards|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=900|publisher=Mellanox|accessdate=Nov 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Economy of the Palestinian territories#Israel-Palestinian high-tech initiatives|Israel-Palestinian high-tech initiatives]]\n* [[List of Israeli companies quoted on the Nasdaq]]\n* [[Silicon Wadi]]\n* [[Startup Village, Yokneam]]\n* [[Economy of Israel]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Israel NASDAQ}}\n{{Electronics industry in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sunnyvale, California]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on TASE]]\n[[Category:Israeli brands]]\n[[Category:American brands]]\n[[Category:Information technology companies of Israel]]\n[[Category:Networking companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Networking hardware companies]]\n[[Category:Semiconductor companies of Israel]]\n[[Category:Mergers and acquisitions of Israeli companies]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:2007 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications equipment vendors]]\n[[Category:Announced technology acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Mellanox Technologies Ltd.\n| logo = Mellanox Technologies logo.svg\n| type = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{NASDAQ|MLNX}}\n| founded = {{start date and age|1999}} in [[Yokneam Illit]], [[Israel]]\n| founders = Eyal Waldman, Shai Cohen, Roni Ashuri, Michael Kagan, Evelyn Landman, Shimon Rottenberg, Eitan Zahavi, Udi Katz, Alon Webman\n| location = [[Sunnyvale, California|Sunnyvale]], [[California]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.mellanox.com/content/pages.php?pg=contact |title=Mellanox office locations |publisher= Mellanox Technologies}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.linkedin.com/company/mellanox-technologies |title=Mellanox Technologies |publisher= Linkedin Corporation}}</ref>\n| key_people = Eyal Waldman, <small>CEO</small>\n| num_employees = 2900 (March 2017)\n| revenue = {{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]863,9 Million <small>(''FY17'')</small>\n{{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]658,1 Million <small>(''FY15'')</small><ref name = CorpFact2>{{cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/financialpost/20160127006351/en/Mellanox-Achieves-Record-Quarterly-Annual-Revenue |title=Mellanox Achieves Record Quarterly and Annual Revenue |publisher=Mellanox Technologies |year=2016 |accessdate=2016-01-27}}</ref>\n{{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]463.6 Million <small>(''FY14'')</small><ref name = CorpFact3>{{cite web|url=http://www.mellanox.com/related-docs/company/MLNX_Corporate_Deck.pdf |title=Corporate Overview |publisher=Mellanox Technologies |year=2015 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n| operating_income = {{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]118.31 Million <small>(''FY12'')</small>\n| net_income = {{profit}} [[United States Dollar|US$]]111.38 Million <small>(''FY12'')</small>\n| parent = \n| industry = Communication equipment\n| products = [[Ethernet]] and [[InfiniBand]] [[switches]] <br> [[host bus adapter]]s\n| homepage = {{URL|www.mellanox.com}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n[[File:MELLANOX - 1024.jpg|thumb|Mellanox Headquarters in [[Yokneam Illit]]]]\n'''Mellanox Technologies Ltd.''' ({{lang-he|\u05de\u05dc\u05d0\u05e0\u05d5\u05e7\u05e1 \u05d8\u05db\u05e0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d5\u05d2\u05d9\u05d5\u05ea \u05d1\u05e2\"\u05de}}) is an [[Israel]]i-American multinational supplier of computer networking products based on [[InfiniBand]] and [[Ethernet]] technology. Mellanox offers adapters, switches, software, cables and silicon for markets including [[High Performance Computing|high-performance computing]], [[data center]]s, [[cloud computing]], [[computer data storage]] and financial services.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nOn March 11, 2019, [[Nvidia]] announced its intent to acquire the company for $6.9 billion.<ref>https://www.engadget.com/2019/03/11/nvidia-acquisition-mellanox/</ref><ref>https://nvidianews.nvidia.com/news/nvidia-to-acquire-mellanox-for-6-9-billion</ref> Other companies willing to acquire Mellanox were [[Intel]], [[Xilinx]] and [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://social.techcrunch.com/2019/03/11/daily-crunch-nvidia-mellanox/|title=Daily Crunch: NVIDIA is buying Mellanox for $6.9B|website=TechCrunch|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n===1999\u20132009===\nMellanox was founded in 1999 by former [[Israelis|Israeli]] executives of Intel Corporation and Galileo Technology (which was acquired by [[Marvell Technology Group]] in October 2000 for $2.8 billion<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4113479/Marvell-to-acquire-LAN-chip-supplier-Galileo-for-2-7-billion-in-stock |title= Marvell to acquire LAN-chip supplier Galileo for $2.7 billion in stock |publisher= eetimes.com |date= 2000-10-17 |accessdate= 2011-06-12 }}</ref>) Eyal Waldman, Shai Cohen, Roni Ashuri, Michael Kagan, Evelyn Landman, Eitan Zahavi, Shimon Rottenberg, Udi Katz and Alon Webman.<ref name=\"CorpFact3\" /> Eyal Waldman founded Mellanox in the Israel city of [[Yokneam Illit|Yokne'am]].<ref name=times-ceo>{{cite news |last=Solomon |first=Shoshanna |date=December 26, 2017 |title=When a startup gets big, the environment gets rougher, says Mellanox CEO |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/for-monday-once-you-become-big-the-environment-can-turn-hostile-mellanox-ceo-for-monday/ | work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Initially founded as an [[integrated circuit]] (chip) manufacturer, it evolved into a producer of complete end-to-end systems by 2009.<ref name=bbg/>  The company raised over $89 million in 3 financing rounds of [[venture capital]].{{When|date=April 2017}}<ref name=globes>{{cite web |url= http://www.globes.co.il/serveen/globes/docview.asp?did=1000685576&fid=1725 |title=Oracle acquires $11m more Mellanox shares |first= Tali |last=Tsipori |publisher= [[Globes]] |date= September 25, 2011 |accessdate= 2011-10-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.crn.com/news/channel-programs/18827937/vc-money-continues-to-drain-into-infiniband-mellanox-secures-56m.htm;jsessionid=p3jwDPOPqFQFywCdlyPgUQ**.ecappj01 |title= VC Money Continues To Drain Into InfiniBand: Mellanox Secures $56M |first= Joseph F. |last= Kovar |publisher=[[CRN Magazine|CRN]] |date= February 11, 2002 |accessdate= 2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nThe company went public in 2007, with an [[initial public offering]] on [[NASDAQ]] that raised $102 million, and valued the company at over half a billion dollars.<ref name=eet1>{{cite news |url= http://www.eetimes.com/electronics-news/4186774/Mellanox-raises-102-million-with-IPO-on-Nasdaq |title= Mellanox raises $102 million with IPO on Nasdaq |first=John |last= Walko |work= [[EE Times]] |date= February 8, 2007 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> Created in 2009, Mellanox's investment fund was publicly launched in 2014.<ref name=globes-a/>\n\n===2010\u2013present===\nIn 2010, [[Oracle Corporation]] became a major investor in the company, holding around 10% of its stock.<ref name=globes/> Oracle uses InfiniBand technology in its [[Exadata]] and Exalogic appliances.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/77108/20101029/oracle-mellanox-hp-dell-ibm-switch-chip-infiniband-siwtches-solaris-sun-acquired.htm |title=Oracle buys 10 pct stake in Mellanox, will Dell, HP, IBM follow suit? |first=Carl |last=Bagh |publisher=[[International Business Times]] |date=October 29, 2010 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101112045944/http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/77108/20101029/oracle-mellanox-hp-dell-ibm-switch-chip-infiniband-siwtches-solaris-sun-acquired.htm |archivedate=November 12, 2010 }}</ref> Stock shares were also listed on the [[Tel Aviv Stock Exchange]], until 2013 when the company de-listed itself, but remained on NASDAQ.<ref>{{Cite news |title= Mellanox Technologies Initiates Process to Delist Ordinary Shares from Tel Aviv Stock Exchange |date= May 30, 2013 |work= Press release |url= http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=1032 |access-date= April 23, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, Mellanox acquired Voltaire Ltd., a provider of data center switches for about $218 million.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=527 |title= Mellanox Technologies, Ltd. Completes Acquisition of Voltaire, Ltd. |work= Press release |date=February 7, 2011 |access-date= April 23, 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"reg2010\" />\n\nIn 2016, Mellanox Technologies began to employ programmers in the [[Gaza Strip]], in addition to its team of [[Israeli Arab]] programmers and programmers in Ramallah and Nablus.<ref>[http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/business/1.725521 Mellanox Hires Programmers in the Gaza Strip]</ref> In 2016, Mellanox had revenues of $857 million.<ref name=times-ceo/> In December 2017, Mellanox announced it would start a new startup accelerator.<ref name=globes-a>{{cite news |last=Habib-Valdhorn |first=Shiri |date= |title=Mellanox to launch startup accelerator |url=http://www.globes.co.il/en/article-mellanox-to-launch-startup-accelerator-1001217054 | work=[[Globes]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Over 2017, shares in the company rose by 55 percent. That year, the company also made its largest acquisition with [[EZchip]].<ref name=times-ceo/>\n\nIn 2019 Mellanox was acquired for $ 6.9 billion by [[Nvidia|Nvidia Corporation]] and it is a definite contender for the largest [[Mergers and acquisitions|M&A]] deal in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/mellanox-technologies-nvidia-to-buy-in-69-billion-deal-2019-3-1028018625|title=Nvidia is buying Mellanox Technologies in a $6.9 billion deal (NVDA) {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=markets.businessinsider.com|access-date=2019-10-05}}</ref>\n\n===Boardroom in 2018===\nThe activist investor [[Starboard Value|Starboard Value LP]] purchased a 10.7% stake in the company in November 2017.<ref name=wsj-starboard/> After acquiring 10.7%, Starboard wrote a letter to the company stating that Starboard attributed the company's \"underperformance compared to other semiconductor companies\" to \"a pattern of weak execution that has included both excessive spending and missed growth opportunities\". The letter called for \"substantial change\".<ref name=toi-solomon>{{cite news |last=Solomon |first=Shoshanna |date=January 8, 2018 |title=Activist investor Starboard calls for \u2018substantial change\u2019 at Israel\u2019s Mellanox |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/activist-investor-starboard-calls-for-substantial-change-at-israels-mellanox/ | work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref><ref name=reuters-aishwarya>{{cite news |last=Venugopal |first=Aishwarya |date=January 8, 2018 |title=Starboard says chipmaker Mellanox's 2018 targets insufficient |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-starboard-mellanox/starboard-says-chipmaker-mellanoxs-2018-targets-insufficient-idUSKBN1EX0YK | work=[[Reuters]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> The day after, on January 9, 2018,<ref name=ti-cut/> Mellanox announced it would immediately discontinue its 1550&nbsp;nm silicon photonics development activities, with president and CEO Eyal Waldman saying the review of the silicon photonics business had started in May 2017.<ref name=optics-org>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=January 10, 2018 |title=Mellanox to cease 1550nm silicon photonics development |url=http://optics.org/news/9/1/6 | work=optics.org |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> Mellanox also said it would fire 100 people, all in the US. At the time, the company employed 2,900 people, mostly in Israel.<ref name=ti-cut>{{cite news |last=Solomon |first=Shoshanna |date=January 10, 2018 |title=Mellanox to cut 100 US jobs as chip line development halted |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/mellanox-to-cut-100-us-jobs-as-chip-line-development-halted/ | work=[[The Times of Israel]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn a \"board battle,\"<ref name=cnbc-stock>{{cite news |last=Schacknow |first=Peter |date=January 18, 2018 |title=Stocks making the biggest moves premarket: MS, WMT, WWW, LQ, AAPL, AA & more |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/18/stocks-making-the-biggest-moves-premarket-ms-wmt-www-lq-aapl-aa-more.html | work=[[CNBC]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> in January 2018, Starboard sent a letter to shareholders asking them to entirely replace the board of directors.<ref name=barrons>{{cite news |last=Ray |first=Tiernan |date=January 18, 2018 |title=Mellanox, Under Siege From Starboard, Surges 6% on Q4 Beat, Outlook |url=https://www.barrons.com/articles/mellanox-under-siege-from-starboard-surges-6-on-q4-beat-outlook-1516314219?tesla=y | work=[[Barron's (newspaper)|Barron's]] |location= |access-date=January 20, 2018}}</ref> On January 17, 2018, it was announced that Starboard was aiming to remove the entire board at Mellanox Technologies. At the time, Mellanox had a $3.3 billion market value.<ref name=wsj-starboard>{{cite news |last=Benoit |first=David |date=January 17, 2018 |title=Starboard Value to Launch Proxy Fight for Entire Board at Mellanox |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/starboard-value-to-launch-proxy-fight-for-entire-board-at-mellanox-1516225802 | work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |location=New York City, New York |access-date=January 18, 2018}}</ref> Starboard said it would nominate nine candidates for election to the company's board, including Starboard head Jeffrey Smith.<ref name=retuers-nine>{{Citation |last= |first= |date=January 17, 2018 |title=Starboard to nominate nine candidates to Mellanox board |publisher=[[Reuters]] |publication-place= |page= |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mellanox-starboard/starboard-to-nominate-nine-candidates-to-mellanox-board-idUSKBN1F702E |accessdate= January 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisitions ===\n\nIn 2013 Mellanox acquired certain [[assets]] of [[XLoom Communications|XLoom Communications Ltd.]], including opto-electric chip-scale packaging, as well as hired XLoom's technology personnel.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}} In July 2013, Mellanox acquired privately held [[Kotura|Kotura, Inc.]], a developer of [[silicon photonics]] optical interconnect technology for high-speed networking.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=1096 | title= Mellanox Technologies, Ltd. Completes Acquisition of Kotura, Inc. | publisher=NASDAQ |accessdate=Aug 15, 2013}}</ref> In July 2013, Mellanox acquired privately held [[IPtronics]] A/S, a designer of optical interconnect components for digital communications.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=1052 | title= Mellanox Technologies, Ltd. Completes Acquisition of IPtronics A/S  | publisher=NASDAQ |accessdate=Jul 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Mellanox acquired privately held [[Integrity Project]], for its software connectivity, low-level development, real-time applications and security technology.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=1321 | title= Mellanox Technologies Ltd. Announces Definitive Agreement to Acquire Integrity Project | publisher=NASDAQ |accessdate=June 24, 2014}}</ref> In February 2016, Mellanox acquired publicly held [[EZchip Semiconductor]], a provider of [[network processor]]s and multi-core processors from EZchip's earlier acquisition of [[Tilera]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n== Manufacturing ==\nMellanox is a [[fabless semiconductor company]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestreet.com/story/10003192/web-chip-fabless-mellanox-poised-to-raise-50m-at-company-value-of-250m.html |title=Web-chip fabless Mellanox poised to raise $50m at company value of $250m |publisher=[[TheMarker]] |date=October 30, 2001 |accessdate=2011-10-29 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The current generation of its chips are produced by [[TSMC|Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Corp]].<ref name=\"switchx\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2011/04/26/mellanox_switchx_switch_chip/|title=Mellanox uncloaks SwitchX network switch-hitter|last=Morgan|first=Timothy Prickett|date=April 26, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-29|publisher=The Register}}</ref>\n\n== Products and market ==\n[[File:MellanoxSC18.jpg|thumb|Mellanox at SC18]]\nMellanox Technologies provides Ethernet and InfiniBand [[Network interface controller|network adapters]], [[Network switch|switches]] and cables for servers and storage used in cloud and enterprise [[data centers]]<ref name=tmc>{{cite web|url=http://10-gigabit-ethernet.tmcnet.com/topics/10-gigabit-ethernet/articles/226214-the-road-with-mellanox-technologies.htm |title=On the Road with Mellanox Technologies |last=Amodio |first=Michelle |publisher=TMCnet |date=October 6, 2011|accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> based on internally developed [[integrated circuit]]s.<ref name=\"reg2010\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/11/29/mellanox_acquires_voltaire/ |title= Mellanox gobbles up Voltaire for $218m |author= Timothy Prickett Morgan |work= [[The Register]] |date= November 29, 2010 |access-date= April 23, 2017}}</ref> Mellanox offers interconnect products: adapters, switches, cables, software and silicon for a range of markets including high-performance computing, enterprise data centers, [[Web 2.0]], cloud, storage and financial services.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn 2010, a press release from [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] described Mellanox as \"the premier [[switched fabric]] provider for enterprise data centers and [[high performance computing]]\". According to the same press release, Mellanox's InfiniBand technology is faster, more scalable and provides higher throughput than alternative communications technologies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.oracle.com/us/corporate/press/183506 |title=Oracle Corporation Makes Strategic Investment In Mellanox Technologies, Ltd. |publisher=[[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]] |date=October 27, 2010 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n[[Larry Ellison]], CEO of Oracle, promoted Mellanox\u2019s InfiniBand technology.<ref name=bbg>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-04/mellanox-ceo-waldman-sees-revenue-growing-10-fold-after-voltaire-purchase.html |title=Mellanox CEO Sees Sales Rising 10-Fold With Voltaire |first=Gwen |last=Ackerman |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]] |date=January 5, 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nMellanox network adapter and switch ASICs support [[Remote direct memory access|RDMA]]/[[RDMA over Converged Ethernet|RoCE]] technology, which are the basis of card and system level products:\n\n*The ConnectX product family of multi-protocol [[Application-specific integrated circuit|ASIC]]<nowiki/>s and adapters supports virtual protocol interconnect, enabling support for both Ethernet and InfiniBand traffic at speeds up to 200Gb/s. The latest ConnectX-6, and ConnectX-6 Dx adapters have enhanced capabilities such as high speed (up to 200Gb per second), OVS acceleration, Multi-Host support, and inline crypto acceleration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/products_dyn?product_family=268&mtag=connectx_6_en_ic|title=ConnectX-6 Product Family|last=|first=|date=|website=Mellanox|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/products_dyn?product_family=302&mtag=connectx_6_dx_ic|title=ConnectX-6 VPI|last=|first=|date=|website=community.mellanox.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2016-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/products_dyn?product_family=302&mtag=connectx_6_dx_ic|title=ConnectX-6 Dx|last=|first=|date=|website=www.mellanox.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref> \n*The ConnectX architecture has been described as \"novel\", with excellent performance that is \"very well suited for modern [[multi-core]] platforms\".<ref>{{cite journal|citeseerx = 10.1.1.81.4890 |title=Performance Analysis and Evaluation of Mellanox ConnectX InfiniBand Architecture with Multi-Core Platforms |first1=Sayantan |last1=Sur |first2=Matthew J. |last2=Koop |last3=Lei |first4=Dhabaleswar K. |last4=Panda |journal=hoti |pages=125\u2013134 |publisher=15th Annual IEEE Symposium on High-Performance Interconnects (HOTI 2007) |year=2007}}</ref> The Quantum family of InfiniBand switches supports up to 40 ports running at HDR 200Gb/s. The Quantum switches offer un-matched latency and packet forwarding performance and support advanced HPC offloads including SHARP (collective operation acceleration) and SHIELD (self-healing) technologies.\n*The Spectrum product family of Ethernet switches.\n*The LinkX product family of cables and transceivers. These products are available in both Ethernet and InfiniBand protocols and SFP, QSFP, OSFP, and DDSFP form factors.\n\n=== High-performance computing ===\nMellanox Technologies' InfiniBand products for [[computer cluster]]s are claimed to be widely deployed in many of the [[TOP500]] list of [[High-performance computing|high-performance computers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=2227|title=Mellanox 200G HDR InfiniBand Accelerates 31% of New InfiniBand Systems on November\u2019s TOP500|last=|first=|date=June 27, 2011|newspaper=Bloomberg|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n=== Storage ===\nMellanox also promotes its products for [[storage area network]]s, and pioneered Ethernet Storage Fabrics (ESF) to replace legacy Fibre Channel SANs (storage area networks).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nextplatform.com/2017/09/26/ascendancy-ethernet-storage-fabrics/|title=The Ascendancy Of Ethernet Storage Fabrics|last=Morgan|first=Timothy Prickett|date=2017-09-26|website=The Next Platform|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>\n\n=== Global Operations ===\nIn addition to its global headquarters in the US, Mellanox has offices in Israel, Denmark, China, Russia, Singapore, Taiwan, Japan and the United Kingdom. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mellanox.com/page/contact?ssn=oaavq86vjgi5sojt4o1dbd9ph7|title=Mellanox Contact Us|website=www.mellanox.com|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Customers ==\n{{As of|2019||df=}} Mellanox had two customers, [[Hewlett-Packard]] and Dell-EMC, both of whom contributed more than 10% of the companies revenues.<ref>https://ir.mellanox.com/node/21816/html</ref>\n\n== Hiring practices ==\nMellanox outsourced some of its engineering to the [[West Bank]]. Rather than setting up offshore engineering centers in the Far East or Eastern Europe, Mellanox hired Palestinian engineers from [[Ramallah]] through a Palestinian outsourcing firm.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.haaretz.com/themarker/high-tech-company-aims-to-be-first-israeli-firm-to-hire-palestinian-engineers-1.323311 |title=High-tech company aims to be first Israeli firm to hire Palestinian engineers |first=Tali |last=Heruti-Sover |publisher=[[Haaretz]] |date=November 7, 2010 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> In 2018, Waldman told a Tel Aviv conference hosted by [[Globes]] magazine that over 100 Palestinians are working on Mellanox projects.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://services.globes.co.il/en/article-mellanox-ceo-we-employ-over-100-palestinians-1001242534|title=Mellanox CEO: We employ over 100 Palestinians|last=Levy|first=Aviv|date=21 June 2018|work=Globes|access-date=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nWaldman had previously talked about Mellanox's plans to  build a research and development center in Ramallah, even though it is more expensive than outsourcing to Eastern Europe.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Middle-East/2011/0422/Tech-diplomacy-Israeli-CEO-hires-Palestinian-programmers |title=Tech diplomacy: Israeli CEO hires Palestinian programmers |first=Joshua |last=Mitnick |publisher=[[The Christian Science Monitor]] |date=April 22, 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n* In November 2012,  Mellanox was named one of the Fastest Growing Companies in Deloitte's 2012 Technology Fast 500 Rankings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mellanox Technologies Ranked Number 364 Fastest Growing Company in North America on Deloitte\u2019s 2012 Technology Fast 500\u2122|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=903|publisher=Mellanox|accessdate=November 14, 2012}}</ref>\n* In November 2012, Mellanox was awarded - 'Readers\u2019 Choice: Best HPC Interconnect Product or Technology' from HPCwire<ref name=HPCwire2012>{{cite web|title=Mellanox Wins Five HPCwire 2012 Readers' and Editors\u2019 Choice Awards|url=http://www.mellanox.com/page/press_release_item?id=900|publisher=Mellanox|accessdate=Nov 13, 2012}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Economy of the Palestinian territories#Israel-Palestinian high-tech initiatives|Israel-Palestinian high-tech initiatives]]\n* [[List of Israeli companies quoted on the Nasdaq]]\n* [[Silicon Wadi]]\n* [[Startup Village, Yokneam]]\n* [[Economy of Israel]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Israel NASDAQ}}\n{{Electronics industry in the United States}}\n\n[[Category:1999 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Sunnyvale, California]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on TASE]]\n[[Category:Israeli brands]]\n[[Category:American brands]]\n[[Category:Information technology companies of Israel]]\n[[Category:Networking companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Networking hardware companies]]\n[[Category:Semiconductor companies of Israel]]\n[[Category:Mergers and acquisitions of Israeli companies]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:2007 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications equipment vendors]]\n[[Category:Announced technology acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProducts and market:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 200Gb/s \u2192 200Gbit/s (2), \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mellanox_Technologies"}
{"title_page": "Black Hawk War", "text_new": "{{use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|1832 conflict between the United States and Native Americans}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Black Hawk War\n|partof=the [[American Indian Wars]]\n|date=April 6 \u2013 August 27, 1832\n|place=[[Illinois]] and [[Michigan Territory]]\n|result=United States victory\n|image= Chief Black Hawk3.jpg\n|caption= Black Hawk, the Sauk war chief and namesake of the Black Hawk War in 1832\n|combatant1={{Flag|United States|1822}}<br/>[[Ho-chunk]] [[Menominee]] [[Sioux|Dakota]] and [[Potawatomi]] allies\n|combatant2=Black Hawk's [[British Band]] with [[Ho-Chunk]] and [[Potawatomi]] allies\n|commander1=[[Henry Atkinson (soldier)|Henry Atkinson]] <br/>[[Edmund P. Gaines]] <br />[[Henry Dodge]] <br />[[Isaiah Stillman]]<br />[[Jefferson Davis]]\n|commander2=[[Black Hawk (Sauk leader)|Black Hawk]] <br />[[Neapope]] <br />[[Wabokieshiek]]\n|strength1=6,000+ [[Militia in the United States|militiamen]] <br />630 [[United States Army|Army regulars]]<br />700+ Native Americans<ref>Hall, 2: Jung, 174</ref>\n|strength2=500 warriors<br />600 non-combatants\n|casualties1=77 killed (including non-combatants)<ref name=\"Jung, 172\" />\n|casualties2=450\u2013600 killed (including non-combatants)<ref name=\"Jung, 172\" /><ref>Eby, 17.</ref>\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Black Hawk War}}\n\nThe '''Black Hawk War''' was a brief  conflict between the [[United States]] and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] led by [[Black Hawk (Sauk leader)|Black Hawk]], a [[Sauk people|Sauk]] leader. The war erupted soon after Black Hawk and a group of Sauks, [[Meskwaki]]s, and [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoos]], known as the \"[[British Band]]\", crossed the [[Mississippi River]], into the U.S. state of [[Illinois]], from [[Iowa|Iowa Indian Territory]] in April 1832. Black Hawk's motives were ambiguous, but he was apparently hoping to avoid bloodshed while resettling on tribal land that had been ceded to the United States in the disputed 1804 [[Treaty of St. Louis (1804)|Treaty of St. Louis]].\n\nU.S. officials, convinced that the British Band was hostile, mobilized a frontier [[Militia in the United States|militia]] and opened fire on a delegation from the Native Americans on May 14, 1832. Black Hawk responded by successfully attacking the militia at the [[Battle of Stillman's Run]]. He led his band to a secure location in what is now southern [[Wisconsin]] and was pursued by U.S. forces. Meanwhile, other Native Americans conducted raids against forts and settlements largely unprotected with the absence of U.S. troops. Some [[Ho-Chunk]] and [[Potawatomi]] warriors with grievances against [[European-Americans]] took part in these raids, although most tribe members tried to avoid the conflict. The [[Menominee]] and [[Sioux|Dakota]] tribes, already at odds with the Sauks and Meskwakis, supported the U.S.\n\nCommanded by General [[Henry Atkinson (soldier)|Henry Atkinson]], the U.S. troops tracked the British Band. Militia under Colonel [[Henry Dodge]] caught up with the British Band on July 21 and defeated them at the [[Battle of Wisconsin Heights]]. Black Hawk's band was weakened by hunger, death, and desertion and many native survivors retreated towards the Mississippi. On August 2, U.S. soldiers attacked the remnants of the British Band at the [[Battle of Bad Axe]], killing many and capturing most who remained alive. Black Hawk and other leaders escaped, but later surrendered and were imprisoned for a year.\n\nThe Black Hawk War gave the young captain [[Abraham Lincoln]] his [[Abraham Lincoln in the Black Hawk War|brief military service]], although he never saw combat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://southernhistorians.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Understanding-the-WBTS-Compiled-Download-Website-Oct-2015.pdf|title=Understanding the war between the States - Chapter 24}}</ref> Other participants who later became famous included [[Winfield Scott]], [[Zachary Taylor]], and [[Jefferson Davis]]. The war gave impetus to the U.S. policy of [[Indian removal]], in which Native American tribes were pressured to sell their lands and move west of the Mississippi River and stay there.\n\n==Background==\nIn the 18th century, the [[Sauk people|Sauk]] and [[Meskwaki]] (or Fox) [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] tribes lived along the [[Mississippi River]] in what are now the U.S. states of [[Illinois]] and [[Iowa]]. The two tribes had become closely connected after having been displaced from the [[Great Lakes region (North America)|Great Lakes region]] in conflicts with [[New France]] and other Native American tribes, particularly after the so-called [[Fox Wars]] ended in the 1730s.<ref>Hall, 21\u201326; Jung, 13\u201314; Trask, 29.</ref> By the time of the Black Hawk War, the population of the two tribes was about 6,000 people.<ref>Jung, 14; Trask, 64.</ref>\n\n===Disputed treaty===\n[[File:Stlouistreatymap1804.png|thumb|The land ceded to the United States in the 1804 [[Treaty of St. Louis (1804)|Treaty of St. Louis]] is shown here in yellow.]]\n\nAs the United States expanded westward in the early 19th century, government officials sought to buy as much Native American land as possible. In 1804, [[Indiana Territory|territorial governor]] [[William Henry Harrison]] negotiated a [[Treaty of St. Louis (1804)|treaty in St. Louis]] in which a group of Sauk and Meskwaki leaders supposedly sold their lands east of the Mississippi for more than $2,200, in goods and annual payments of $1,000 in goods. The treaty became controversial because the Native leaders had not been authorized by their tribal councils to cede lands. Historian Robert Owens argued that the chiefs probably did not intend to give up ownership of the land, and that they would not have sold so much valuable territory for such a modest price.<ref>Owens, 87\u201390.</ref> Historian Patrick Jung concluded that the Sauk and Meskwaki chiefs intended to cede a little land, but that the Americans included more territory in the treaty's language than the Natives realized.<ref>Jung, 21\u201322.</ref> According to Jung, the Sauks and Meskwakis did not learn the true extent of the cession until years later.<ref>Jung, 32.</ref>\n\nThe 1804 treaty allowed the tribes to continue using the ceded land until it was sold to American settlers by the U.S. government.<ref>Trask, 72.</ref> For the next two decades, Sauks continued to live at [[Saukenuk]], their primary village, which was located near the confluence of the Mississippi and [[Rock River (Mississippi River)|Rock Rivers]].<ref>Trask, 28\u201329.</ref> In 1828, the U.S. government finally began to have the ceded land surveyed for white settlement. [[Indian agent]] [[Thomas Forsyth (Indian agent)|Thomas Forsyth]] informed the Sauks that they should vacate Saukenuk and their other settlements east of the Mississippi.<ref>Trask, 70; Jung, 52\u201353.</ref>\n\n===Sauks divided===\nThe Sauks were divided about whether to resist implementation of the disputed 1804 treaty.<ref>Jung, 52.</ref> Most Sauks decided to relocate west of the Mississippi rather than become involved in a confrontation with the United States. The leader of this group was [[Keokuk (Sauk leader)|Keokuk]], who had helped defend Saukenuk against the Americans during the [[War of 1812]]. Keokuk was not a chief, but as a skilled orator, he often spoke on behalf of the Sauk civil chiefs in negotiations with the Americans.<ref>Jung, 55.</ref> Keokuk regarded the 1804 treaty as a fraud, but after having seen the size of American cities on the east coast in 1824, he did not think the Sauks could successfully oppose the United States.<ref>Jung, 54\u201355; Nichols, 78.</ref>\n\nAlthough the majority of the tribe decided to follow Keokuk's lead, about 800 Sauks\u2014roughly one-sixth of the tribe\u2014chose instead to resist American expansion.<ref name=\"Jung, 56\">Jung, 56.</ref> [[Black Hawk (Sauk leader)|Black Hawk]], a war captain who had fought against the United States in the War of 1812 and was now in his 60s, emerged as the leader of this faction in 1829.<ref>Jung, 53.</ref> Like Keokuk, Black Hawk was not a civil chief, but he became Keokuk's primary rival for influence within the tribe. Black Hawk had actually signed a treaty in May 1816 that affirmed the disputed 1804 land cession, but he insisted that what had been written down was different from what had been spoken at the treaty conference. According to Black Hawk, the \"whites were in the habit of saying one thing to the Indians and putting another thing down on paper.\"<ref>Jung, 53; Trask, 73.</ref>\n\n[[File:Keokuk1.jpg|thumb|upright|left|alt=Native American chief in regalia|Keokuk by [[George Catlin]], c. 1830s]]\n\nBlack Hawk was determined to hold onto Saukenuk, a village at the confluence of the Rock River with the Mississippi, where he lived and had been born. When the Sauks returned to the village in 1829 after their annual winter hunt in the west, they found that it had been occupied by white squatters who were anticipating the sale of land.<ref>Hall, 90; Trask, 71.</ref> After months of clashes with the squatters, the Sauks left in September 1829 for the next winter hunt. Hoping to avoid further confrontations, Keokuk told Forsyth that he and his followers would not return to Saukenuk.<ref>Trask, 79.</ref>\n\nAgainst the advice of Keokuk and Forsyth, Black Hawk's faction returned to Saukenuk in the spring of 1830.<ref>Jung, 59.</ref> This time, they were joined by more than 200 [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoos]], a people who had often allied with the Sauks.<ref>Jung, 47, 58.</ref> Black Hawk and his followers became known as the \"[[British Band]]\" because they sometimes flew a British flag to defy claims of U.S. sovereignty, and because they hoped to gain the support of the British at [[Fort Malden]] in Canada.<ref>Hall, 90, 127; Jung, 56.</ref>\n[[File:Black Hawk 1831 newspaper.jpg|thumb|Newspaper account of the alarm caused by Sauk returning to [[Saukenuk]], ''Washington National Intelligencer'', June 13, 1831]]\nWhen the British Band once again returned to Saukenuk in 1831, Black Hawk's following had grown to about 1,500 people, and now included some [[Potawatomi]]s,<ref>Jung, 60.</ref> a people with close ties to the Sauks and Meskwakis.<ref>Edmunds, 235\u201336.</ref> American officials determined to force the British Band out of the state. General [[Edmund P. Gaines]], commander of the Western Department of the [[United States Army]], assembled troops with the hope of intimidating Black Hawk into leaving. The army had no cavalry to pursue the Sauks should they flee further into Illinois on horseback, and so on June 5 Gaines requested that the state [[Militia in the United States|militia]] provide a mounted battalion.<ref>Eby, 83\u201386.</ref> Illinois governor [[John Reynolds (Illinois politician)|John Reynolds]] had already alerted the militia; about 1,500 volunteers turned out.<ref>Eby, 88; Jung, 62.</ref> Meanwhile, Keokuk convinced many of Black Hawk's followers to leave Illinois.<ref>Jung, 62.</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 1831, Gaines sent troops to [[Vandruff Island]] across from Saukenuk. The island had been named for a farmer and trader who operated a ferry, as well as sold liquor to the natives, which had previously prompted a raid by Black Hawk to destroy the whiskey.<ref>http://www.rockislandpreservation.org/postcards-from-home/view-of-vandruff-island-from-black-hawk-tower/</ref> This time, underbrush had grown to impede the militiamen from landing, so the next day the militia tried to assault Saukenuk itself, only to find that Black Hawk and his followers had abandoned the village and recrossed the Mississippi.<ref>Eby, 88\u201389; Jung, 63; Trask, 102.</ref> On June 30, Black Hawk, [[Quashquame]], and other Sauk leaders met with Gaines and signed an agreement in which the Sauks promised to remain west of the Mississippi and to break off further contact with the British in Canada.<ref>Jung, 64; Trask, 105.</ref>\n\n==Black Hawk's return==\nBlack Hawk did not remain west of the Mississippi for long. In late 1831, [[Neapope]], a Sauk civil chief, returned from Fort Malden and told Black Hawk that the British and the other Illinois tribes were prepared to support the Sauks against the United States. Why Neapope made these claims, which would prove to be unfounded, is unclear. Historians have described Neapope's report to Black Hawk as \"wishful thinking\"<ref>Hall, 116.</ref> and the product of a \"fertile imagination\".<ref name=\"Jung, 66\">Jung, 66.</ref> Black Hawk welcomed the information, though he would later criticize Neapope for misleading him. He spent the winter in an unsuccessful attempt to recruit additional allies from other tribes and from Keokuk's followers.<ref>Jung, 69; Hall, 116.</ref>\n\nAccording to Neapope's erroneous report, [[Wabokieshiek]] (\"White Cloud\"), a shaman known to Americans as the \"Winnebago Prophet\", had claimed that other tribes were ready to support Black Hawk.<ref name=\"Jung, 66\"/> Wabokieshiek's mother was a [[Ho-Chunk]] (Winnebago), but his father had belonged to a Sauk clan that provided the tribe's civil leaders. When Wabokieshiek joined the British Band in 1832, he would become the ranking Sauk civil chief in the group.<ref>Jung, 74.</ref> His village, [[Prophetstown, Illinois|Prophetstown]], was about thirty-five miles up the Rock River from Saukenuk.<ref>Trask, 63, 69.</ref> The village was inhabited by about 200<ref name=\"Jung, 56\"/> Ho-Chunks, Sauks, Meskwakis, Kickapoos, and Potawatomis who were dissatisfied with tribal leaders who refused to stand up to American expansion.<ref>Dowd, 193; Hall, 110.</ref> Although some Americans would later characterize Wabokieshiek as a primary instigator of the Black Hawk War, the Winnebago Prophet, according to historian John Hall, \"actually discouraged his followers from resorting to armed conflict with the whites\".<ref>Hall, 110.</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 1832, the British Band entered Illinois once again.<ref>Jung, 74; Hall, 116; Trask, 145, gives a more general date of \"probably April 6\".</ref> Numbering about 500 warriors and 600 non-combatants, they crossed near the mouth of the [[Iowa River]] over to Yellow Banks (present-day [[Oquawka, Illinois]]), and then headed north.<ref>Jung, 74\u201375; Trask, 145.</ref> Black Hawk's intentions upon reentering Illinois are not entirely clear, since reports from both white and Indian sources are conflicting. Some said that the British Band intended to reoccupy Saukenuk, while others said that the destination was Prophetstown.<ref>Trask, 149\u201350; Hall, 129\u201330.</ref> According to historian Kerry Trask, \"even Black Hawk may not have been sure where they were going and what they intended to do\".<ref>Trask, 150.</ref>\n\nAs the British Band moved into Illinois, American officials urged Wabokieshiek to advise Black Hawk to turn back. Previously, the Winnebago Prophet had encouraged Black Hawk to come to Prophetstown, arguing that the 1831 agreement made with General Gaines prohibited a return to Saukenuk, but did not  forbid the Sauks from moving to Prophetstown.<ref>Jung, 73; Trask, 146\u201347.</ref> Now, instead of telling Black Hawk to turn back, Wabokieshiek told him that, as long as the British Band remained peaceful, the Americans would have no choice but to let them settle at Prophetstown, especially if the British and the area tribes supported the band.<ref>Hall, 110; Jung, 73.</ref> Although the British Band traveled with armed guards as a security precaution, Black Hawk was probably hoping to avoid a war when he reentered Illinois. The presence of women, children, and the elderly indicated that the band was not a war party.<ref>Eby, 35; Jung, 74\u201375.</ref>\n\n==Intertribal war and American policy==\nAlthough the return of Black Hawk's band worried U.S. officials, they were at the time more concerned about the possibility of a war among the Native American tribes in the region.<ref>Jung 50, 70; Hall, 99\u2013100.</ref> Most accounts of the Black Hawk War focus on the conflict between Black Hawk and the United States, but historian John Hall argues that this overlooks the perspective of many Native American participants. According to Hall, \"the Black Hawk War also involved an intertribal conflict that had smoldered for decades\".<ref>Hall, 9.</ref> Tribes along the Upper Mississippi had long fought for control of diminishing hunting grounds, and the Black Hawk War provided an opportunity for some Natives to resume a war that had nothing to do with Black Hawk.<ref>Hall, 100.</ref>\n\nAfter having displaced the British as the dominant outside power following the War of 1812, the United States had assumed the role of mediator in intertribal disputes. Before the Black Hawk War, U.S. policy discouraged intertribal warfare. This was not strictly for humanitarian reasons: intertribal warfare made it more difficult for the United States to acquire Indian land and move the tribes to the West, a policy known as [[Indian removal]], which had become the primary goal by the late 1820s.<ref>Hall, 55, 95; Buckley, 165.</ref> U.S. efforts at mediation included multi-tribal treaty councils at [[Prairie du Chien]] in [[First Treaty of Prairie du Chien|1825]] and [[Fourth Treaty of Prairie du Chien|1830]], in which tribal boundaries were drawn.<ref>Buckley, 172\u201375; Hall, 77\u201378, 100\u201302.</ref> Native Americans sometimes resented American mediation, especially young men, for whom warfare was an important avenue of social advancement.<ref>Hall, 9, 24, 55, 237.</ref>\n\n[[File:Fort armstrong.JPG|thumb|left|[[Fort Armstrong, Illinois|Fort Armstrong]] was located on Rock Island, which is now known as [[Rock Island Arsenal|Arsenal Island]]. The view is from the Illinois side, with Iowa in the background.]]\n\nThe situation was complicated by the American [[spoils system]]. After [[Andrew Jackson]] assumed the [[President of the United States|U.S. presidency]] in March 1829, many competent [[Indian agent]]s were replaced by unqualified Jackson loyalists, argues historian John Hall. Men like [[Thomas Forsyth (Indian agent)|Thomas Forsyth]], [[John Marsh (pioneer)|John Marsh]], and [[Thomas McKenney]] were replaced by less qualified men such as [[Felix St. Vrain]]. In the 19th century, historian [[Lyman Draper]] argued that the Black Hawk War could have been avoided had Forsyth remained as the agent to the Sauks.<ref>Hall, 103\u201304. Eby, 79, echoed the argument.</ref>\n\nIn 1830, violence threatened to undo American attempts at preventing intertribal warfare. In May, Dakotas ([[Santee Sioux]]) and [[Menominee]]s killed fifteen Meskwakis attending a treaty conference at Prairie du Chien. In retaliation, a party of Meskwakis and Sauks killed twenty-six Menominees, including women and children, at Prairie du Chien in July 1831.<ref>Jung, 49; Hall, 111.</ref> American officials discouraged the Menominees from seeking revenge, but the western bands of the tribe formed a coalition with the Dakotas to strike at the Sauks and Meskwakis.<ref>Hall, 113\u201315.</ref>\n\nHoping to prevent the outbreak of a wider war, American officials ordered the U.S. Army to arrest the Meskwakis who massacred the Menominees.<ref>Hall, 115; Jung, 49\u201350.</ref> General Gaines was ill, and so his subordinate, Brigadier General [[Henry Atkinson (soldier)|Henry Atkinson]], received the assignment.<ref>Hall, 115; Jung, 70.</ref> Atkinson was a middle-aged officer who had ably handled administrative and diplomatic tasks, most notably during the 1827 [[Winnebago War]], but he had never seen combat.<ref>Hall, 115; Jung, 71\u201372; Trask, 143.</ref> On April 8, he set out from [[Jefferson Barracks]] in Missouri, moving up the Mississippi River by steamboat with about 220 soldiers. By chance, Black Hawk and his British Band had just crossed into Illinois. Although Atkinson did not realize it, his boats passed Black Hawk's band.<ref>Trask, 146.</ref>\n\nWhen Atkinson arrived at [[Fort Armstrong, Illinois|Fort Armstrong]] on [[Rock Island Arsenal|Rock Island]] on April 12, he learned that the British Band was in Illinois, and that most of the Meskwakis he wanted to arrest were now with the band.<ref>Hall, 117; Jung, 75.</ref> Like other American officials, Atkinson was convinced that the British Band intended to start a war. Because he had few troops at his disposal, Atkinson hoped to get support from the Illinois state militia. He wrote to Governor Reynolds on April 13, describing\u2014and perhaps purposely exaggerating\u2014the threat that the British Band posed.<ref>Jung, 76; Trask, 158\u201359.</ref> Reynolds, who was eager for a war to drive the Indians out of the state, responded as Atkinson had hoped: he called for militia volunteers to assemble at [[Beardstown, Illinois|Beardstown]] by April 22 to begin a thirty-day enlistment. The 2,100 men who volunteered were organized into a brigade of five regiments under Brigadier General [[Samuel Whiteside]].<ref>Jung, 79\u201380; Trask, 174.</ref> Among the militiamen was [[Abraham Lincoln in the Black Hawk War|23-year-old Abraham Lincoln]], who was elected captain of his company.<ref>Jung, 79.</ref>\n\n==Initial diplomacy==\n[[File:Shabbona (chief)1.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Potawatomi]] chief [[Shabbona]] tried to keep his tribe out of the war.]]\n\nAfter Atkinson's arrival at Rock Island on April 12, 1832, he, Keokuk, and Meskwaki chief [[Wapello (chief)|Wapello]] sent emissaries to the British Band, which was now ascending the Rock River. Black Hawk rejected the messages advising him to turn back.<ref>Jung, 76\u201377; Nichols, 117\u201318.</ref> Colonel [[Zachary Taylor]], a regular army officer who served under Atkinson, later stated that Atkinson should have made an attempt to stop the British Band by force. Some historians have agreed, arguing that Atkinson could have prevented the outbreak of war with more decisive action or astute diplomacy. Cecil Eby charged that \"Atkinson was a paper general, unwilling to proceed until all risk had been eliminated\".<ref>Eby, 93.</ref> Kerry Trask, however, argued that Atkinson was correct in believing that he did not yet have enough troops to stop the British Band.<ref>Trask, 152\u201355.</ref> According to Patrick Jung, leaders on both sides had little chance of avoiding bloodshed at this point, because the militiamen and some of Black Hawk's warriors were spoiling for a fight.<ref>Jung, 86.</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Black Hawk learned that the [[Ho-Chunk]] and [[Potawatomi]] tribes were less supportive than anticipated. As in other tribes, different bands of these tribes often pursued different policies.<ref>Hall, 10\u201311.</ref> The Ho-Chunks who lived along the Rock River in Illinois had family ties to the Sauks; they cautiously supported the British Band while trying not to provoke the Americans.<ref>Hall, 131.</ref> Ho-Chunks in Wisconsin were more divided. Some bands, remembering their loss to the Americans in the 1827 [[Winnebago War]], decided to stay clear of the conflict. Other Ho-Chunks with ties to the Dakotas and Menominees, most notably [[Waukon Decorah]] and his brothers, were eager to fight against the British Band.<ref>Hall, 122\u201323; Jung, 78\u201379.</ref>\n\nMost Potawatomis wanted to remain neutral in the conflict, but found it difficult to do so.<ref>Hall, 125.</ref> Many white settlers, recalling the [[Fort Dearborn massacre]] of 1812, distrusted the Potawatomis and assumed that they would join Black Hawk's uprising.<ref>Hall, 122.</ref> Potawatomi leaders worried that the tribe as a whole would be punished if any Potawatomis supported Black Hawk. At a council outside Chicago on May 1, 1832, Potawatomi leaders including [[Billy Caldwell]] \"passed a resolution declaring any Potawatomi who supported Black Hawk a traitor to his tribe\".<ref>Hall, 132.</ref> In mid May, Potawatomi chiefs [[Shabonna]] and [[Waubonsie]] told Black Hawk that neither they nor the British would come to his aid.<ref>Jung, 86\u201387; Edmunds, 236.</ref>\n\nWithout British supplies, adequate provisions, or Native allies, Black Hawk realized that his band was in serious trouble.<ref>Jung, 83\u201384; Nichols, 120; Trask, 180\u201381.</ref> By some accounts, he was ready to negotiate with Atkinson to end the crisis, but an ill-fated encounter with Illinois militiamen would end all possibility of a peaceful resolution.<ref>Hall, 133.</ref>\n\n==Stillman's Run==\n{{main|Battle of Stillman's Run}}\n[[File:Major Isaiah Stillman.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Isaiah Stillman]], militia commander at the [[Battle of Stillman's Run]]]]\n\nGeneral [[Samuel Whiteside]]'s militia brigade had been mustered into federal service at Rock Island under General Atkinson in late April, and divided into a scout or spy battalion commanded by [[James D. Henry]], as well as four regiments (commanded by Colonels John DeWitt, Jacob Fry, John Thomas and Samuel M. Thompson),<ref>Harrington, George B. Past and Present of [[Bureau County, Illinois]]. Chicago, IL, USA: Pioneer Publishing (1906) p. 39 </ref> with judge William Thomas as their quartermaster. Atkinson had allowed Reynolds, Whiteside, and the militiamen to leave up the Rock River on April 27, while he brought up the rear with the regular soldiers, directing his least trained and disciplined men\u2014to \"move upon the Indians should they be within striking distance without waiting for my arrival\".<ref name=\"Jung, 84\">Jung, 84.</ref><ref>[[Thomas Ford (politician)|Thomas Ford]], A History of Illinois: from its commencement as a state in 1818 to 1847 (annotated and introduced by Rodney O Davis; University of Illinois Press 1995) pp. 76-77</ref> Governor Reynolds accompanied the expedition as a major general of militia. \n\nOn May 10 the militia marching up the Rock River in pursuit of the British Band reached Prophetstown (about 35 miles from their starting point at the confluence). Rather than wait per Atkinson's plan, they burned White Cloud's empty village before proceeding about 40 miles upriver to Dixon's Ferry, where they waited for Atkinson and his troops.<ref>Prophetstown State Park brochure, available at https://www.dnr.illinois.gov/publications/Documents/00000097.pdf</ref><ref>Ford p. 78</ref> Although Reynolds wanted to allow the 260 eager militiamen not yet federalized to continue further as scouts, the cautious Whiteside insisted on waiting for Atkinson at the settlement.<ref>Jung, 85\u201386.</ref> Dixon's Ferry had actually been established in 1826 by Ogee, of half-native ancestry, where the wagon trail connecting Peoria to the lead mines in Galena crossed the Rock River; settlers has established cabins along the Peoria/Galena trace and at the crossing, so that by 1829 its post office served settlers up the river as far as Rockford.<ref>William V. Pooley, Settlement of Illinois, 1830-1850 (Thesis submitted to the University of Wisconsin in 1905; printed at Ann Arbor, Michigan, University Microfilms in 1968) p. 147</ref>\n\nOn May 12, learning that Black Hawk's band was only twenty-five miles away, eager militiamen led by Major [[Isaiah Stillman]] left Whiteside's encampment, making another camp on a tributary of the Rock River later named  [[Stillman Valley, Illinois|Stillman Valley]] after him. Seeing a small party of natives with a red flag, Major Samuel Hackelton and some men pursued without waiting for orders, and Hackelton killed a native before returning to Whiteside's camp with the news.<ref>Ford p. 78</ref> However, Black Hawk and others were nearby, and near dusk on May 14 attacked Stillman's party in what became known as the [[Battle of Stillman's Run]]. Accounts of the battle vary.<ref>Jung, 88; Trask, 183.</ref> Black Hawk later stated that he sent three men under a white flag to parley, but the Americans imprisoned them and opened fire on a second group of emissaries who followed. Some militiamen claimed they never saw a white flag; others believed that the flag was a ruse the Indians used to set an ambush.<ref>Jung, 88\u201389; Trask, 186.</ref> All accounts agree that Black Hawk's warriors attacked the militia camp at dusk, that the much more numerous militia were routed, and stragglers reached Whiteside's camp. To Black Hawk's surprise, his forty warriors killed twelve Illinois militiamen; his British Band suffered only three fatalities.<ref>Jung, 89; Hall, 133\u201334.</ref>\n\nThe Battle of Stillman's Run proved a turning point. Before the battle, Black Hawk had not committed to war. Now he determined to avenge what he saw as the treacherous killing of his warriors under a flag of truce.<ref>Jung, 89.</ref> Whiteside too was incensed when he returned to the battle site with a burial party and viewed the mutilated corpses. <ref>\"Battle of Stillman's Run\" in William B. Kessell, Encyclopedia of Native American Wars and Warfare (2005), available online</ref>  After Stillman's defeat, American leaders like President Jackson and [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Lewis Cass]] refused to consider a diplomatic solution; they wanted a resounding victory over Black Hawk to serve as an example to other Native Americans who might consider similar uprisings.<ref>Jung, 118\u201320.</ref>\n\n==Initial raids==\n{| style=\"text-align:center; float:right; clear:right\"\n|-\n| {{Black Hawk War Map}}\n|-\n|Map of Black Hawk War sites<br />[[File:Red Battle X.png|8px|link=]] <small>Battle (with name)</small> [[File:Red pog.svg|7px|link=]] <small>Fort / settlement</small> [[File:Green pog.svg|7px|link=]] <small>Native village</small><br /><small>Symbols are wikilinked to article</small>\n|}\n\nWith hostilities now underway, and few allies to depend upon, Black Hawk sought a place of refuge for the women, children, and elderly in his band. Accepting an offer from the Rock River Ho-Chunks, the band traveled further upriver to [[Lake Koshkonong]] in the [[Michigan Territory]] and camped in an isolated place known as the \"Island\".<ref>Jung, 93\u201394.</ref> With the non-combatants secure, members of the British Band, with a number of Ho-Chunk and Potawatomi allies, began raiding white settlers.<ref>Jung, 94, 108.</ref> Not all Native Americans in the region supported this turn of events; most notably, Potawatomi chief [[Shabonna]] rode throughout the settlements, warning whites of the impending attacks.<ref>Edmunds, 237; Trask, 200; Jung, 95.</ref>\n\nThe initial raiding parties consisted primarily of Ho-Chunk and Potawatomi warriors. The first attack came on May 19, 1832, when Ho-Chunks [[Buffalo Grove ambush|ambushed six men]] near [[Buffalo Grove, Illinois (Ogle County)|Buffalo Grove, Illinois]], killing a man named William Durley.<ref>Jung, 95; Trask, 198.</ref> Durley's [[scalping|scalped]] and mutilated body was found by Indian agent [[Felix St. Vrain]]. The Indian agent was himself [[St. Vrain massacre|killed and mutilated]], along with three other men, several days later at [[Kellogg's Grove]].<ref>Jung, 97; Trask, 198\u201399.</ref>\n\nThe Ho-Chunks and Potawatomis who took part in the war were sometimes motivated by grievances not directly related to Black Hawk's objectives.<ref name=\"Jung, 95\">Jung, 95.</ref> One such incident was the [[Indian Creek massacre]]. In the spring of 1832, Potawatomis living along Indian Creek were upset that a settler named William Davis had dammed the creek, preventing fish from reaching their village. Davis ignored the protests, and assaulted a Potawatomi man who tried to dismantle the dam.<ref>Hall, 135\u201336.</ref> The Black Hawk War provided the Indian Creek Potawatomis with an opportunity for revenge. On May 21, about fifty Potawatomis and three Sauks from the British Band attacked Davis's settlement, killing, scalping, and mutilating fifteen men, women, and children.<ref>Jung, 95; Trask, 202.</ref> Two teenage girls from the settlement were kidnapped and taken to Black Hawk's camp.<ref>Jung, 96; Trask, 215.</ref> A Ho-Chunk chief named White Crow negotiated their release two weeks later.<ref>Trask, 212\u201317.</ref> Like other Rock River Ho-Chunks, White Crow was trying to placate the Americans while clandestinely aiding the British Band.<ref>Hall, 152\u201354; 164\u201365.</ref>\n\n==American reorganization==\nNews of Stillman's defeat, the Indian Creek massacre, and other smaller attacks triggered panic among the white population. Many settlers fled to [[Chicago]], then a small town, which became overcrowded with hungry refugees.<ref>Trask, 200\u201306; Jung, 97.</ref> Many Potawatomis also fled towards Chicago, not wanting to get caught in the conflict nor be mistaken for hostiles.<ref>Edmunds, 238; Jung, 103.</ref> Throughout the region, settlers hurriedly organized militia units and built small forts.<ref>Jung, 96.</ref>\n\nAfter Stillman's defeat on May 14, the regulars and militia continued up the Rock River to search for Black Hawk. The militiamen became discouraged at not being able to find the British Band. When they heard about the Indian raids, many deserted so that they could return home to defend their families.<ref>Trask, 194\u201396.</ref> As morale plummeted, Governor Reynolds asked his militia officers to vote on whether to continue the campaign. General Whiteside, disgusted with the performance of his men, cast the tie-breaking vote in favor of disbanding.<ref>Jung, 100; Trask, 196.</ref> Most of Whiteside's brigade disbanded at [[Ottawa, Illinois]], on May 28. About 300 men, including Abraham Lincoln, agreed to remain in the field for twenty more days until a new militia force could be organized.<ref>Jung, 101; Trask, 196\u201397.</ref>\n\nAs Whiteside's brigade disbanded, Atkinson organized a new force in June 1832 that he dubbed the \"Army of the Frontier\".<ref>Jung, 115.</ref> The army consisted of 629 regular army infantrymen and 3,196 mounted militia volunteers. The militia was divided into three brigades commanded by Brigadier Generals [[Alexander Posey (general)|Alexander Posey]], [[Milton Alexander]], and [[James D. Henry]]. Since many men were assigned to local patrols and guard duties, Atkinson had only 450 regulars and 2,100 militiamen available for campaigning.<ref>Jung, 114\u201315.</ref> Many more militiamen served in units that were not part of the Army of the Frontier's three brigades. Abraham Lincoln, for example, reenlisted as a private in an independent company that was taken into federal service. [[Henry Dodge]], a Michigan territorial militia colonel who would prove to be one of the best commanders in the war,<ref>Jung, 103.</ref> fielded a battalion of mounted volunteers that numbered 250 men at its strongest. The overall number of militiamen who took part in the war is not precisely known; the total from Illinois alone has been estimated at six to seven thousand.<ref>Jung, 116.</ref>\n\nIn addition to organizing a new militia army, Atkinson also began to recruit Native American allies, reversing the previous American policy of trying to prevent intertribal warfare.<ref>Hall, 143\u201345.</ref> Menominees, Dakotas, and some Ho-Chunks bands were eager to go to war against the British Band. By June 6, agent [[Joseph M. Street]] had assembled about 225 Natives at Prairie du Chien.<ref>Hall, 148.</ref> This force included about eighty Dakotas under [[Wapasha II|Wabasha]] and L'Arc, forty Menominees, and several bands of Ho Chunks.<ref>Hall, 148; Jung 104.</ref> Although the Indian warriors followed their own leaders, Atkinson placed the force under the nominal command of [[William S. Hamilton]], a militia colonel and a son of [[Alexander Hamilton]]. Hamilton would prove to be an unfortunate choice to lead the force; historian John Hall characterized him as \"pretentious and unqualified\".<ref>Hall, 145.</ref> Before long, the Indians became frustrated with marching around under Hamilton and not seeing any action. Some Menominee scouts remained, but most of the Natives eventually left Hamilton and fought the war on their own terms.<ref>Hall, 162\u201363; Jung, 105.</ref>\n\n==June raids==\nIn June 1832, after hearing that Atkinson was forming a new army, Black Hawk began sending out raiding parties. Perhaps hoping to lead the Americans away from his camp at Lake Koshkonong, he targeted areas to the west.<ref>Jung, 108.</ref> The first major attack occurred on June 14 near present-day [[South Wayne, Wisconsin]], when a band of about 30 warriors attacked a group of farmers, [[Spafford Farm massacre|killing and scalping four]].<ref>Jung, 109.</ref>\n\n[[File:Pecatonica Battleground1.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Painting of rolling hills, a river, and trees|An 1857 painting of the battlefield at Horseshoe Bend]]\n\nResponding to this attack, militia Colonel Henry Dodge gathered a force of twenty-nine mounted volunteers and set out in pursuit of the attackers. On June 16, Dodge and his men cornered about eleven of the raiders at a bend in the [[Pecatonica River]]. In a brief battle, the Americans killed and scalped all of the Natives.<ref>Jung, 109\u201310; Trask, 233\u201334.</ref> The [[Battle of Horseshoe Bend (1832)|Battle of Horseshoe Bend]] (or Battle of Pecatonica) was the first real American victory in the war, and helped restore public confidence in the volunteer militia force.<ref>Jung, 110; Trask, 234\u201337.</ref>\n\nOn the same day of Dodge's victory, another skirmish took place at [[Kellogg's Grove]] in present-day [[Stephenson County, Illinois]]. American forces had occupied Kellogg's Grove in an effort to intercept war parties raiding to the west. In the [[First Battle of Kellogg's Grove]], militia commanded by [[Adam W. Snyder]] pursued a British Band raiding party of about thirty warriors. Three Illinois militiamen and six Native warriors died in the fighting.<ref>Jung, 111\u201312.</ref> Two days later, on June 18, militia under [[James W. Stephenson]] encountered what was probably the same war party near [[Yellow Creek (Illinois)|Yellow Creek]]. The [[Battle of Waddams Grove]] became a hard fought, hand-to-hand melee. Three militiamen and five or six Indians were killed in the action.<ref>Jung, 112; Trask, 220\u201321.</ref>\n\nBack on June 6, when a civilian miner was killed by raiders near the village of [[Blue Mounds, Wisconsin|Blue Mounds]] in the Michigan Territory, residents began to fear that the Rock River Ho-Chunks were joining the war.<ref>Trask, 220.</ref> On June 20, a Ho-Chunk raiding party estimated by one eyewitness to be as large as 100 warriors [[Attacks at Fort Blue Mounds|attacked the settler fort]] at Blue Mounds. Two militiamen were killed in the attack, one of whom was badly mutilated.<ref>Jung, 112; Trask, 220.</ref>\n\n[[File:Elizabeth Il Apple River Fort2.JPG|thumb|right|alt=A wooden stockade fronted by a wall of vertically-placed logs and a corner blockhouse|Replica of Apple River Fort in Elizabeth, Illinois]]\n\nOn June 24, 1832, Black Hawk and about 200 warriors attacked at the hastily constructed [[Apple River Fort]], near present-day [[Elizabeth, Illinois]]. Local settlers, warned of Black Hawk's approach, took refuge in the fort, which was defended by about 20<ref name=\"Trask, 222\">Trask, 222.</ref> to 35<ref>Jung, 113.</ref> militiamen. The [[Battle of Apple River Fort]] lasted about forty-five minutes. The women and girls inside the fort, under the direction of [[Elizabeth Armstrong (settler)|Elizabeth Armstrong]], loaded muskets and molded bullets.<ref name=\"Trask, 222\"/> After losing several men, Black Hawk broke off the siege, looted the nearby homes, and headed back towards his camp.<ref>Jung, 114.</ref>\n\nThe next day, June 25, Black Hawk's party encountered a militia battalion commanded by Major [[John Dement]]. In the [[Second Battle of Kellogg's Grove]], Black Hawk's warriors drove the militiamen inside their fort and commenced a two-hour siege. After losing nine warriors and killing five militiamen, Black Hawk broke off the siege and returned to his main camp at Lake Koshkonong.<ref>Jung, 121\u201323.</ref> This would prove to be Black Hawk's last military success in the war. With his band running low on food, he decided to take them back across the Mississippi.<ref>Jung, 124.</ref>\n\n==Final campaign==\nOn June 15, 1832, President [[Andrew Jackson]], displeased with Atkinson's handling of the war, appointed General [[Winfield Scott]] to take command.<ref>Jung, 118; Trask, 272.</ref> Scott gathered about 950 troops from eastern army posts just as a [[Second cholera pandemic|cholera pandemic]] had spread to eastern North America.<ref>Jung, 139.</ref> As Scott's troops traveled by steamboat from [[Buffalo, New York]], across the Great Lakes towards Chicago, his men started getting sick from cholera, with many of them dying. At each place the vessels landed, the sick were deposited and soldiers deserted. By the time the last steamboat landed in Chicago, Scott had only about 350 effective soldiers left.<ref>Jung, 140\u201341; Trask, 271\u201375.</ref> On July 29, Scott began a hurried journey west, ahead of his troops, eager to take command of what was certain to be the war's final campaign, but he would be too late to see any combat.<ref>Jung, 141; Trask, 276.</ref>\n\nGeneral Atkinson, who learned in early July that Scott would be taking command, hoped to bring the war to a successful conclusion before Scott's arrival.<ref>Jung, 130.</ref> The Americans had difficulty locating the British Band, however, thanks in part to false intelligence given to them by area Native Americans. Potawatomis and Ho-Chunks in Illinois, many of whom had sought to remain neutral in the war, decided to cooperate with the Americans. Tribal leaders knew that some of their warriors had aided the British Band, and so they hoped that a highly visible show of support for the Americans would dissuade U.S. officials from punishing the tribes after the conflict was over. Wearing white headbands to distinguish themselves from hostile Natives, Ho-Chunks and Potawatomis served as guides for Atkinson's army.<ref>Edmunds, 239; Hall, 244\u201349.</ref> Ho-Chunks sympathetic to the plight of Black Hawk's people misled Atkinson into thinking that the British Band was still at Lake Koshkonong. While Atkinson's men were trudging through the swamps and running low on provisions, the British Band had in fact relocated miles to the north.<ref>Jung, 131\u201334.</ref> Potawatomis under Billy Caldwell also managed to demonstrate support for the Americans while avoiding battle.<ref>Hall, 165\u201367.</ref>\n\nIn mid-July, Colonel Dodge learned from m\u00e9tis trader Pierre Paquette that the British Band was camped near the Rock River rapids, at present [[Hustisford, Wisconsin]].<ref>Jung, 142.</ref> Dodge and [[James D. Henry]] set out in pursuit from [[Fort Winnebago]] on July 15.<ref>Jung, 144.</ref> The British Band, reduced to fewer than 600 people due to death and desertion, headed for the Mississippi River as the militia approached.<ref>Jung, 146\u201348.</ref> The Americans pursued them, killing and scalping several Native stragglers along the way.<ref>Jung, 149\u201350.</ref>\n\n===Wisconsin Heights===\n{{Main|Battle of Wisconsin Heights}}\n\nOn July 21, 1832, the militiamen caught up with the British Band near present-day [[Sauk City, Wisconsin]]. To buy time for the noncombatants to cross the Wisconsin River, Black Hawk and Neapope confronted the Americans in a rear guard action that became known as the [[Battle of Wisconsin Heights]]. Black Hawk was desperately outnumbered, leading about 50 Sauks and 60 to 70 Kickapoos against 750 militiamen.<ref>Jung, 153\u201356.</ref> The battle was a lopsided victory for the militiamen, who lost only one man while killing as many as 68 of Black Hawk's warriors.<ref>Jung, 156; Trask, 260\u201361.</ref> Despite the high casualties, the battle allowed much of the British Band, including many women and children, to escape across the river.<ref name=\"lewis\">{{cite web|url=http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/page2c.html |title=The Black Hawk War of 1832 |last=Lewis |first=James |work=Abraham Lincoln Digitization Project |publisher=Northern Illinois University |page=2c |accessdate=2009-08-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815021319/http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/page2c.html |archivedate=2009-08-15 }}</ref> Black Hawk had managed to hold off a much larger force while allowing most of his people to escape, a difficult military operation that impressed some U.S. Army officers when they learned of it.<ref>Jung, 157.</ref>\n\nThe Battle of Wisconsin Heights had been a victory for the militia; no regular soldiers of the U.S. Army had been present.<ref>Jung, 156.</ref> Atkinson and the regulars joined up with the volunteers several days after the battle. With a force of about 400 regulars and 900 militiamen, the Americans crossed the Wisconsin River on July 27 and resumed the pursuit of the British Band.<ref>Jung, 161; Trask, 268.</ref> The British Band was moving slow, encumbered with wounded warriors and people dying of starvation. The Americans followed the trail of dead bodies, cast off equipment, and the remains of horses the hungry Natives had eaten.<ref>Jung, 162; Trask, 270\u201371.</ref>\n\n===Bad Axe===\n{{Main|Battle of Bad Axe}}\n\nAfter the Battle of Wisconsin Heights, a messenger from Black Hawk had shouted to the militiamen that the starving British Band was going back across the Mississippi and would fight no more. No one in the American camp understood the message, however, since their Ho-Chunk guides were not present to interpret.<ref>Nichols, 131; Trask, 266.</ref> Black Hawk may have believed that the Americans had gotten the message, and that they had not pursued him after the Battle of Wisconsin Heights. He apparently expected that the Americans were going to let his band recross the Mississippi unmolested.<ref>Jung, 168\u201369.</ref>\n\n[[File: Battle of Bad Axe.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Native American women and children fleeing for their lives, preparing to cross the Mississippi River, during Black Hawk's defeat at the [[Battle of Bad Axe]]]]\n\nThe Americans, however, had no intentions of letting the British Band escape. The [[Warrior (steamboat)|''Warrior'']], a steamboat outfitted with an artillery piece, patrolled the Mississippi River, while American-allied Dakotas, Menominees, and Ho-Chunks watched the banks.<ref>Hall, 192\u201394.</ref> On August 1, the ''Warrior'' arrived at the mouth of the [[Bad Axe River]], where the Dakotas told the Americans that they would find Black Hawk's people.<ref>Jung, 164\u201365; Hall, 194.</ref> Black Hawk raised a white flag in an attempt to surrender, but his intentions may have been garbled in translation.<ref>Jung, 165; Nichols, 133.</ref> The Americans, in no mood to accept a surrender anyway, thought that the Indians were using the white flag to set an ambush. When they became certain that the Natives on land were the British Band, they opened fire. Twenty-three Natives were killed in the exchange of gunfire, while just one soldier on the ''Warrior'' was injured.<ref>Jung, 166; Trask, 279.</ref>\n\n[[File:1832 Battle of Bad Axe and steamboat Warrior.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The steamboat ''[[Warrior (steamboat)|Warrior]]'' firing upon escaping Native Americans trying to get across the Mississippi River to safety in Iowa]]\n\nAfter the ''Warrior'' left, Black Hawk decided to seek refuge in the north with the [[Ojibwe]]s. Only about 50 people, including Wabokieshiek, agreed to go with him; the others remained, determined to cross the Mississippi and return to Sauk territory.<ref>Jung, 166; Nichols, 133. Jung says \"about 60 people\" left with Black Hawk; Nichols, 135, estimated \"perhaps forty\".</ref> The next morning, on August 2, Black Hawk was heading north when he learned that the American army had closed in on the members of the British Band who were trying to cross the Mississippi.<ref name=\"Jung, 169\">Jung, 169.</ref> He tried to rejoin the main body, but after a skirmish with American troops near present-day [[Victory, Wisconsin]], he gave up the attempt.<ref name=\"Jung, 169\"/> Sauk chief [[Weesheet]] later criticized Black Hawk and Wabokieshiek for abandoning the people during the final battle of the war.<ref>Jung, 180\u201381; Trask, 282.</ref>\n\nThe [[Battle of Bad Axe]] began at about 9:00 am on August 2 after the Americans caught up with the remnants of the British Band a few miles downstream from the mouth of the Bad Axe River. The British Band was reduced to roughly 500 people by this time, including about 150 warriors.<ref>Jung, 170.</ref> The warriors fought with the Americans while the Native noncombatants frantically tried to cross the river. Many made it to one of the two nearby islands, but were dislodged after the steamboat ''Warrior'' returned at noon, carrying regulars and Menominees allied with the Americans.<ref>Trask, 286\u201387; Jung, 170\u201371.</ref>\n\nThe battle was another lopsided victory for the Americans, who lost just 14 men, including one Menominee who died by [[friendly fire]] and was buried with honors alongside the white soldiers.<ref>Jung, 171\u201372; Hall, 196.</ref> At least 260 members of the British Band were killed, including about 110 who drowned while trying to cross the river. Although the regular soldiers of the U.S. Army generally tried to avoid needless bloodshed, many of the militiamen intentionally killed Native noncombatants, sometimes in cold blood.<ref>Trask, 285\u201386, 293.</ref> The encounter was, in the words of historian Patrick Jung, \"less of a battle and more of a massacre\".<ref name=\"Jung, 172\"/>\n\nMenominees from [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]], who had mobilized a battalion of nearly 300 men, arrived too late for the battle. They were upset at having missed the chance to fight their old enemies, and so on August 10, General Scott sent 100 of them after a part of the British Band that had escaped.<ref>Hall, 197.</ref> Indian agent Samuel C. Stambaugh, who accompanied them, urged the Menominees not to take any scalps, but Chief Grizzly Bear insisted that such a prohibition could not be enforced.<ref>Hall, 198.</ref> The group tracked down about ten Sauks, only two of whom were warriors. The Menominees killed and scalped the warriors, but spared the women and children.<ref>Hall, 199.</ref>\n\nThe Dakotas, who had volunteered 150 warriors to fight against the Sauks and Meskwakis, also arrived too late to participate in the Battle of Bad Axe, but they pursued the members of the British Band who made it across the Mississippi into Iowa. On about August 9, in the final engagement of the war,<ref>Hall, 202.</ref> they attacked the remnants of the British Band along the [[Cedar River (Iowa River)|Cedar River]], killing 68 and taking 22 prisoners.<ref>Jung, 175; Hall, 201.</ref> Ho-Chunks also hunted survivors of the British Band, taking between fifty and sixty scalps.<ref>Jung, 177; Hall, 210\u201311.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Black Hawk War resulted in the deaths of 77 white settlers, militiamen, and regular soldiers.<ref name=\"Jung, 172\">Jung, 172.</ref> This figure does not include the deaths from cholera suffered by the relief force under General Winfield Scott. Estimates of how many members of the British Band died during the conflict range from about 450 to 600, or about half of the 1,100 people who entered Illinois with Black Hawk in 1832.<ref>Jung, 172, 179.</ref>\n\nA number of American men with political ambitions fought in the Black Hawk War. At least seven future [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]]s took part, as did four future Illinois governors; future governors of Michigan, Nebraska, and the [[Wisconsin Territory]]; and one future U.S. president.<ref name=\"lewis2d\">{{cite web|url=http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/page2d.html|title=The Black Hawk War of 1832|last=Lewis|first=James|work=Abraham Lincoln Historical Digitization Project|publisher=Northern Illinois University|page=2d|accessdate=2009-08-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619071514/http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/page2d.html|archivedate=2009-06-19}}</ref> The Black Hawk War demonstrated to American officials the need for mounted troops to fight a mounted foe. During the war, the U.S. Army did not have cavalry; the only mounted soldiers were part-time volunteers. After the war, Congress created the [[US Army Rangers#Black Hawk War|Mounted Ranger Battalion]] under the command of [[Henry Dodge]], which was expanded to the [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Cavalry Regiment]] in 1833.<ref>Jung 205\u201306.</ref>\n\n===Black Hawk's imprisonment and legacy===\n[[File:Black hawk statue.jpg|thumb|Statue of Black Hawk, [[Black Hawk State Historic Site]]]]\n\nAfter the Battle of Bad Axe, Black Hawk, Wabokieshiek, and their followers traveled northeast to seek refuge with the Ojibwes. American officials offered a reward of $100 and forty horses for Black Hawk's capture.<ref>Jung, 181.</ref> While camping near present-day [[Tomah, Wisconsin]], Black Hawk's party was seen by a passing Ho-Chunk man, who alerted his village chief. The village council sent a delegation to Black Hawk's camp and convinced him to surrender to the Americans. On August 27, 1832, Black Hawk and Wabokieshiek surrendered at Prairie du Chien to Indian agent Joseph Street.<ref>Jung, 182; Trask, 294\u201395.</ref> Colonel Zachary Taylor took custody of the prisoners, and sent them by steamboat to Jefferson Barracks, escorted by Lieutenants [[Jefferson Davis]] and [[Robert Anderson (Civil War)|Robert Anderson]].<ref>Jung, 183.</ref>\n\nBy war's end, Black Hawk and nineteen other leaders of the British Band were incarcerated at Jefferson Barracks. Most of the prisoners were released in the succeeding months, but in April 1833, Black Hawk, Wabokieshiek, Neapope, and three others were transferred to [[Fort Monroe]] in Virginia, which was better equipped to hold prisoners.<ref>Jung, 190\u201391.</ref> The American public was eager to catch a glimpse of the captured Indians. Large crowds gathered in [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] and [[Cincinnati]] to watch them pass.<ref>Trask, 298; Jung, 192.</ref> On April 26, the prisoners met briefly with President Jackson in [[Washington, D.C.]], before being taken to Fort Monroe.<ref>Jung, 192; Trask, 298.</ref> Even in prison they were treated as celebrities: they posed for portraits by artists such as [[Charles Bird King]] and [[John Wesley Jarvis]], and a dinner was held in their honor before they left.<ref>Nichols, 147; Trask, 298.</ref>\n\nAmerican officials decided to release the prisoners after a few weeks. First, however, the Natives were required to visit several large U.S. cities on the east coast. This was a tactic often used when Native American leaders came to the East, because it was thought that a demonstration of the size and power of the United States would discourage future resistance to U.S. expansion.<ref>Jung, 191; Nichols, 148; Trask, 300.</ref> Beginning on June 4, 1833, Black Hawk and his companions were taken on a tour of [[Baltimore]], [[Philadelphia]], and [[New York City]]. They attended dinners and plays, and were shown a battleship, various public buildings, and a military parade. Huge crowds gathered to see them. Black Hawk's handsome son Nasheweskaska (Whirling Thunder) was a particular favorite.<ref>Jung, 195\u201397; Nichols, 148\u201349; Trask, 300\u201301.</ref> Reaction in the west, however, was less welcoming. When the prisoners traveled through [[Detroit]] on their way home, one crowd burned and hanged [[effigies]] of the Indians.<ref>Trask, 301\u201302; Jung, 197.</ref>\n\nAccording to historian Kerry Trask, Black Hawk and his fellow prisoners were treated like celebrities because the Indians served as a living embodiment of the [[noble savage]] myth that had become popular in the eastern United States. Then and later, argues Trask, white Americans absolved themselves of complicity in the dispossession of Native Americans by expressing admiration or sympathy for defeated Indians like Black Hawk.<ref>Trask, 298\u2013303.</ref> The mythologizing of Black Hawk continued, argues Trask, with the many plaques and memorials that were later erected in his honor. \"Indeed,\" writes Trask, \"most of the reconstructed memory of the Black Hawk War has been designed to make white people feel good about themselves.\"<ref>Trask, 308.</ref> Black Hawk also became an admired symbol of resistance among Native Americans, even among descendants of those who had opposed him.\n\n===Treaties and removals===\nThe Black Hawk War marked the end of Native armed resistance to U.S. expansion in the [[Northwest Territory|Old Northwest]]<ref>Buckley, 210; Hall, 255; Jung, 208.</ref> The war provided an opportunity for American officials such as Andrew Jackson, Lewis Cass, and John Reynolds to compel Native American tribes to sell their lands east of the Mississippi River and move to the West, a policy known as [[Indian removal]]. Officials conducted a number of treaties after the war to purchase the remaining Native American land claims in the Old Northwest. The Dakotas and Menominees, who won approval from American officials for their role in the war, largely avoided postwar removal pressure until later decades.<ref>Hall, 207.</ref>\n\nAfter the war, American officials learned that some Ho-Chunks had aided Black Hawk more than had been previously known.<ref>Hall, 209\u201310.</ref> Eight Ho-Chunks were briefly imprisoned at Fort Winnebago for their role in the war, but charges against them were eventually dropped due to a lack of witnesses.<ref>Jung, 207.</ref> In September 1832, General Scott and Governor Reynolds conducted a treaty with the Ho-Chunks at Rock Island. The Ho-Chunks ceded all their land south of the Wisconsin River in exchange for a forty-mile strip of land in Iowa and annual payments of $10,000 for twenty-seven years.<ref>Hall, 212\u201313; Jung, 285\u201386.</ref> The land in Iowa was known as the \"Neutral Ground\" because it had been designated in 1830 as a buffer zone between the Dakotas and their enemies to the south, the Sauks and Meskwakis.<ref>Jung, 49; Buckley, 203.</ref> Scott hoped that the settlement of the Ho-Chunks in the Neutral Ground would help keep the peace.<ref name=\"Jung, 186\">Jung, 186.</ref> Ho-Chunks remaining in Wisconsin were pressured to sign a removal treaty in 1837, even though leaders such as Waukon Decorah had been U.S. allies during the Black Hawk War. General Atkinson was assigned to use the army to forcibly relocate those Ho-Chunks who refused to move to Iowa.<ref>Hall, 259\u201361.</ref>\n\nFollowing the September 1832 treaty with the Ho-Chunks, Scott and Reynolds conducted another with the Sauks and Meskwakis, with Keokuk and Wapello serving as the primary representatives of their tribes. Scott told the assembled chiefs that \"if a particular part of a nation goes out of their country, and makes war, the whole nation is responsible\".<ref name=\"Jung, 186\"/> The tribes sold about 6 million acres (24,000&nbsp;km\u00b2) of [[Black Hawk Purchase|land in eastern Iowa]] to the United States for payments of $20,000 per year for thirty years, among other provisions.<ref>Trask, 304; Jung, 187.</ref> Keokuk was granted a [[Indian reservation|reservation]] within the cession and recognized by the Americans as the primary chief of the Sauks and Meskwakis.<ref>Jung, 187.</ref> The tribes sold the reservation to the United States in 1836, and additional land in Iowa the following year.<ref>Jung, 198.</ref> Their last lands in Iowa were sold in 1842, and most of the Natives moved to a reservation in Kansas.<ref>Jung, 201\u201302.</ref>\n\nThanks to the decision of Potawatomi leaders to aid the U.S. during the war, American officials did not seize tribal land as [[war reparations]]. Instead, only three individuals accused of leading the Indian Creek massacre were tried in court; they were acquitted.<ref>Edmunds, 238; Hall, 208, 215.</ref> Nevertheless, the drive to purchase Potawatomi land west of the Mississippi began in October 1832, when [[Treaty of Tippecanoe|commissioners in Indiana]] bought a large amount of Potawatomi land, even though not all Potawatomi bands were represented at the treaty.<ref>Hall, 215\u201316.</ref> The tribe was compelled to sell their remaining land west of the Mississippi in a [[Treaty of Chicago|treaty held in Chicago]] in September 1833.<ref>Edmunds, 247\u201348; Hall, 231.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Black Hawk War}}\n* [[Abraham Lincoln in the Black Hawk War]]\n* [[Second Black Hawk War]]\n* [[American Indian Wars]]\n* [[Sixty Years' War]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n===Secondary sources===\n* Buckley, Jay H. ''William Clark: Indian Diplomat''. Norman, Oklahoma: University of Oklahoma Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-8061-3911-1}}; {{ISBN|0-8061-3911-0}}.\n* Eby, Cecil. ''\"That Disgraceful Affair\", The Black Hawk War''. New York: Norton, 1973. {{ISBN|0-393-05484-5}}.\n* Edmunds, R. David. ''The Potawatomis: Keepers of the Fire''. University of Oklahoma Press, 1978. {{ISBN|0-8061-1478-9}}\n* Hall, John W. ''Uncommon Defense: Indian Allies in the Black Hawk War''. Harvard University Press, 2009. {{ISBN|0-674-03518-6}}.\n* Jung, Patrick J. ''The Black Hawk War of 1832''. Norman, Oklahoma: University of Oklahoma Press, 2007. {{ISBN|0-8061-3811-4}}.\n* Nichols, Roger L. ''Black Hawk and the Warrior's Path''. Arlington Heights, Illinois: Harlan Davidson, 1992. {{ISBN|0-88295-884-4}}.\n* Nichols, Roger L. ''Warrior Nations: The United States and Indian Peoples.'' Norman, OK: University of Oklahoma Press, 2013.\n* Owens, Robert M. ''Mr. Jefferson's Hammer: William Henry Harrison and the Origins of American Indian Policy''. Norman, Oklahoma: University of Oklahoma Press, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-8061-3842-8}}.\n* Trask, Kerry A. ''Black Hawk: The Battle for the Heart of America''. New York: Henry Holt and Company, 2006. {{ISBN|0-8050-7758-8}}.\n\n===Primary sources===\n* Black Hawk. ''Life of Black Hawk''. Originally published 1833. Reprinted often in various editions. Revised in 1882 with inauthentic embellishments; most modern editions restore the original wording.\n* Whitney, Ellen M., ed. ''The Black Hawk War, 1831\u20131832: Volume I, Illinois Volunteers''. Springfield, Illinois: Illinois State Historical Library, 1970. {{ISBN|0-912154-22-5}}. Published as Volume XXXV of ''Collections of the Illinois State Historical Library''. Available [https://archive.org/details/blackhawkwar183135whit online] from the [[Internet Archive]].\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014, ed. ''The Black Hawk War, 1831\u20131832: Volume II, Letters & Papers, Part I, April 30, 1831 \u2013 June 23, 1832''. Springfield, Illinois: Illinois State Historical Library, 1973. {{ISBN|0-912154-22-5}}. Published as Volume XXXVI of ''Collections of the Illinois State Historical Library''. Available [https://archive.org/details/blackhawkwar183136whit online] from the Internet Archive.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014, ed. ''The Black Hawk War, 1831\u20131832: Volume II, Letters & Papers, Part II, June 24, 1832 \u2013 October 14, 1834''. Springfield, Illinois: Illinois State Historical Library, 1975. {{ISBN|0-912154-24-1}}. Published as Volume XXXVII of ''Collections of the Illinois State Historical Library''.\n* \u2014\u2014\u2014, ed. ''The Black Hawk War, 1831\u20131832: Volume II, Letters and Papers, Part III, Appendices and Index.'' Springfield, Illinois: Illinois State Historical Library, 1978. Published as Volume XXXVIII of ''Collections of the Illinois State Historical Library''.\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box|onlinebooks=yes}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081208200253/http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/index.html The Black Hawk War of 1832], Abraham Lincoln Historical Digitization Project\n* [http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/turningpoints/tp-012/ Turning Points in Wisconsin History: The Black Hawk War] (documents from the Wisconsin Historical Society)\n* [http://www.pritzkermilitary.org/whats_on/pritzker-military-presents/john-w-hall-uncommon-defense/ Webcast Lecture] at the [[Pritzker Military Museum & Library]] by John W. Hall on March 27, 2010\n* [http://cdm15999.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/p15999coll24/id/37160 George Peacock diary, MSS 1228], at [[L. Tom Perry Special Collections]], [[Harold B. Lee Library]], [[Brigham Young University]]. Includes Peacock's recollection of incidents from the Black Hawk War. \n\n{{Black Hawk War (1832)}}\n{{Illinois conflicts}}\n{{good article}}\n\n\n[[Category:Black Hawk War| ]]\n[[Category:Sac and Fox]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1832]]\n[[Category:Wars between the United States and Native Americans]]\n[[Category:Native American history of Illinois]]\n[[Category:Native American history of Michigan]]\n[[Category:Native American history of Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Military history of Michigan]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Illinois]]\n[[Category:1832 in the United States]]\n[[Category:1830s in Illinois]]\n[[Category:1830s in Michigan Territory]]\n[[Category:1830s in Wisconsin Territory]]\n", "text_old": "{{use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{short description|1832 conflict between the United States and Native Americans}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n|conflict=Black Hawk War\n|partof=the [[American Indian Wars]]\n|date=April 6 \u2013 August 27, 1832\n|place=[[Illinois]] and [[Michigan Territory]]\n|result=United States victory\n|image= Chief Black Hawk3.jpg\n|caption= Black Hawk, the Sauk war chief and namesake of the Black Hawk War in 1832\n|combatant1={{Flag|United States|1822}}<br/>[[Ho-chunk]] [[Menominee]] [[Sioux|Dakota]] and [[Potawatomi]] allies\n|combatant2=Black Hawk's [[British Band]] with [[Ho-Chunk]] and [[Potawatomi]] allies\n|commander1=[[Henry Atkinson (soldier)|Henry Atkinson]] <br/>[[Edmund P. Gaines]] <br />[[Henry Dodge]] <br />[[Isaiah Stillman]]<br />[[Jefferson Davis]]\n|commander2=[[Black Hawk (Sauk leader)|Black Hawk]] <br />[[Neapope]] <br />[[Wabokieshiek]]\n|strength1=6,000+ [[Militia in the United States|militiamen]] <br />630 [[United States Army|Army regulars]]<br />700+ Native Americans<ref>Hall, 2: Jung, 174</ref>\n|strength2=500 warriors<br />600 non-combatants\n|casualties1=77 killed (including non-combatants)<ref name=\"Jung, 172\" />\n|casualties2=450\u2013600 killed (including non-combatants)<ref name=\"Jung, 172\" /><ref>Eby, 17.</ref>\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Black Hawk War}}\n\nThe '''Black Hawk War''' was a brief  conflict between the [[United States]] and [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] led by [[Black Hawk (Sauk leader)|Black Hawk]], a [[Sauk people|Sauk]] leader. The war erupted soon after Black Hawk and a group of Sauks, [[Meskwaki]]s, and [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoos]], known as the \"[[British Band]]\", crossed the [[Mississippi River]], into the U.S. state of [[Illinois]], from [[Iowa|Iowa Indian Territory]] in April 1832. Black Hawk's motives were ambiguous, but he was apparently hoping to avoid bloodshed while resettling on tribal land that had been ceded to the United States in the disputed 1804 [[Treaty of St. Louis (1804)|Treaty of St. Louis]].\n\nU.S. officials, convinced that the British Band was hostile, mobilized a frontier [[Militia in the United States|militia]] and opened fire on a delegation from the Native Americans on May 14, 1832. Black Hawk responded by successfully attacking the militia at the [[Battle of Stillman's Run]]. He led his band to a secure location in what is now southern [[Wisconsin]] and was pursued by U.S. forces. Meanwhile, other Native Americans conducted raids against forts and settlements largely unprotected with the absence of U.S. troops. Some [[Ho-Chunk]] and [[Potawatomi]] warriors with grievances against [[European-Americans]] took part in these raids, although most tribe members tried to avoid the conflict. The [[Menominee]] and [[Sioux|Dakota]] tribes, already at odds with the Sauks and Meskwakis, supported the U.S.\n\nCommanded by General [[Henry Atkinson (soldier)|Henry Atkinson]], the U.S. troops tracked the British Band. Militia under Colonel [[Henry Dodge]] caught up with the British Band on July 21 and defeated them at the [[Battle of Wisconsin Heights]]. Black Hawk's band was weakened by hunger, death, and desertion and many native survivors retreated towards the Mississippi. On August 2, U.S. soldiers attacked the remnants of the British Band at the [[Battle of Bad Axe]], killing many and capturing most who remained alive. Black Hawk and other leaders escaped, but later surrendered and were imprisoned for a year.\n\nThe Black Hawk War gave the young captain [[Abraham Lincoln]] his [[Abraham Lincoln in the Black Hawk War|brief military service]], although he never saw combat.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://southernhistorians.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Understanding-the-WBTS-Compiled-Download-Website-Oct-2015.pdf|title=Understanding the war between the States - Chapter 24}}</ref> Other participants who later became famous included [[Winfield Scott]], [[Zachary Taylor]], and [[Jefferson Davis]]. The war gave impetus to the U.S. policy of [[Indian removal]], in which Native American tribes were pressured to sell their lands and move west of the Mississippi River and stay there.\n\n==Background==\nIn the 18th century, the [[Sauk people|Sauk]] and [[Meskwaki]] (or Fox) [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] tribes lived along the [[Mississippi River]] in what are now the U.S. states of [[Illinois]] and [[Iowa]]. The two tribes had become closely connected after having been displaced from the [[Great Lakes region (North America)|Great Lakes region]] in conflicts with [[New France]] and other Native American tribes, particularly after the so-called [[Fox Wars]] ended in the 1730s.<ref>Hall, 21\u201326; Jung, 13\u201314; Trask, 29.</ref> By the time of the Black Hawk War, the population of the two tribes was about 6,000 people.<ref>Jung, 14; Trask, 64.</ref>\n\n===Disputed treaty===\n[[File:Stlouistreatymap1804.png|thumb|The land ceded to the United States in the 1804 [[Treaty of St. Louis (1804)|Treaty of St. Louis]] is shown here in yellow.]]\n\nAs the United States expanded westward in the early 19th century, government officials sought to buy as much Native American land as possible. In 1804, [[Indiana Territory|territorial governor]] [[William Henry Harrison]] negotiated a [[Treaty of St. Louis (1804)|treaty in St. Louis]] in which a group of Sauk and Meskwaki leaders supposedly sold their lands east of the Mississippi for more than $2,200, in goods and annual payments of $1,000 in goods. The treaty became controversial because the Native leaders had not been authorized by their tribal councils to cede lands. Historian Robert Owens argued that the chiefs probably did not intend to give up ownership of the land, and that they would not have sold so much valuable territory for such a modest price.<ref>Owens, 87\u201390.</ref> Historian Patrick Jung concluded that the Sauk and Meskwaki chiefs intended to cede a little land, but that the Americans included more territory in the treaty's language than the Natives realized.<ref>Jung, 21\u201322.</ref> According to Jung, the Sauks and Meskwakis did not learn the true extent of the cession until years later.<ref>Jung, 32.</ref>\n\nThe 1804 treaty allowed the tribes to continue using the ceded land until it was sold to American settlers by the U.S. government.<ref>Trask, 72.</ref> For the next two decades, Sauks continued to live at [[Saukenuk]], their primary village, which was located near the confluence of the Mississippi and [[Rock River (Mississippi River)|Rock Rivers]].<ref>Trask, 28\u201329.</ref> In 1828, the U.S. government finally began to have the ceded land surveyed for white settlement. [[Indian agent]] [[Thomas Forsyth (Indian agent)|Thomas Forsyth]] informed the Sauks that they should vacate Saukenuk and their other settlements east of the Mississippi.<ref>Trask, 70; Jung, 52\u201353.</ref>\n\n===Sauks divided===\nThe Sauks were divided about whether to resist implementation of the disputed 1804 treaty.<ref>Jung, 52.</ref> Most Sauks decided to relocate west of the Mississippi rather than become involved in a confrontation with the United States. The leader of this group was [[Keokuk (Sauk leader)|Keokuk]], who had helped defend Saukenuk against the Americans during the [[War of 1812]]. Keokuk was not a chief, but as a skilled orator, he often spoke on behalf of the Sauk civil chiefs in negotiations with the Americans.<ref>Jung, 55.</ref> Keokuk regarded the 1804 treaty as a fraud, but after having seen the size of American cities on the east coast in 1824, he did not think the Sauks could successfully oppose the United States.<ref>Jung, 54\u201355; Nichols, 78.</ref>\n\nAlthough the majority of the tribe decided to follow Keokuk's lead, about 800 Sauks\u2014roughly one-sixth of the tribe\u2014chose instead to resist American expansion.<ref name=\"Jung, 56\">Jung, 56.</ref> [[Black Hawk (Sauk leader)|Black Hawk]], a war captain who had fought against the United States in the War of 1812 and was now in his 60s, emerged as the leader of this faction in 1829.<ref>Jung, 53.</ref> Like Keokuk, Black Hawk was not a civil chief, but he became Keokuk's primary rival for influence within the tribe. Black Hawk had actually signed a treaty in May 1816 that affirmed the disputed 1804 land cession, but he insisted that what had been written down was different from what had been spoken at the treaty conference. According to Black Hawk, the \"whites were in the habit of saying one thing to the Indians and putting another thing down on paper.\"<ref>Jung, 53; Trask, 73.</ref>\n\n[[File:Keokuk1.jpg|thumb|upright|left|alt=Native American chief in regalia|Keokuk by [[George Catlin]], c. 1830s]]\n\nBlack Hawk was determined to hold onto Saukenuk, a village at the confluence of the Rock River with the Mississippi, where he lived and had been born. When the Sauks returned to the village in 1829 after their annual winter hunt in the west, they found that it had been occupied by white squatters who were anticipating the sale of land.<ref>Hall, 90; Trask, 71.</ref> After months of clashes with the squatters, the Sauks left in September 1829 for the next winter hunt. Hoping to avoid further confrontations, Keokuk told Forsyth that he and his followers would not return to Saukenuk.<ref>Trask, 79.</ref>\n\nAgainst the advice of Keokuk and Forsyth, Black Hawk's faction returned to Saukenuk in the spring of 1830.<ref>Jung, 59.</ref> This time, they were joined by more than 200 [[Kickapoo people|Kickapoos]], a people who had often allied with the Sauks.<ref>Jung, 47, 58.</ref> Black Hawk and his followers became known as the \"[[British Band]]\" because they sometimes flew a British flag to defy claims of U.S. sovereignty, and because they hoped to gain the support of the British at [[Fort Malden]] in Canada.<ref>Hall, 90, 127; Jung, 56.</ref>\n[[File:Black Hawk 1831 newspaper.jpg|thumb|Newspaper account of the alarm caused by Sauk returning to [[Saukenuk]], ''Washington National Intelligencer'', June 13, 1831]]\nWhen the British Band once again returned to Saukenuk in 1831, Black Hawk's following had grown to about 1,500 people, and now included some [[Potawatomi]]s,<ref>Jung, 60.</ref> a people with close ties to the Sauks and Meskwakis.<ref>Edmunds, 235\u201336.</ref> American officials determined to force the British Band out of the state. General [[Edmund P. Gaines]], commander of the Western Department of the [[United States Army]], assembled troops with the hope of intimidating Black Hawk into leaving. The army had no cavalry to pursue the Sauks should they flee further into Illinois on horseback, and so on June 5 Gaines requested that the state [[Militia in the United States|militia]] provide a mounted battalion.<ref>Eby, 83\u201386.</ref> Illinois governor [[John Reynolds (U.S. politician)|John Reynolds]] had already alerted the militia; about 1,500 volunteers turned out.<ref>Eby, 88; Jung, 62.</ref> Meanwhile, Keokuk convinced many of Black Hawk's followers to leave Illinois.<ref>Jung, 62.</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 1831, Gaines sent troops to [[Vandruff Island]] across from Saukenuk. The island had been named for a farmer and trader who operated a ferry, as well as sold liquor to the natives, which had previously prompted a raid by Black Hawk to destroy the whiskey.<ref>http://www.rockislandpreservation.org/postcards-from-home/view-of-vandruff-island-from-black-hawk-tower/</ref> This time, underbrush had grown to impede the militiamen from landing, so the next day the militia tried to assault Saukenuk itself, only to find that Black Hawk and his followers had abandoned the village and recrossed the Mississippi.<ref>Eby, 88\u201389; Jung, 63; Trask, 102.</ref> On June 30, Black Hawk, [[Quashquame]], and other Sauk leaders met with Gaines and signed an agreement in which the Sauks promised to remain west of the Mississippi and to break off further contact with the British in Canada.<ref>Jung, 64; Trask, 105.</ref>\n\n==Black Hawk's return==\nBlack Hawk did not remain west of the Mississippi for long. In late 1831, [[Neapope]], a Sauk civil chief, returned from Fort Malden and told Black Hawk that the British and the other Illinois tribes were prepared to support the Sauks against the United States. Why Neapope made these claims, which would prove to be unfounded, is unclear. Historians have described Neapope's report to Black Hawk as \"wishful thinking\"<ref>Hall, 116.</ref> and the product of a \"fertile imagination\".<ref name=\"Jung, 66\">Jung, 66.</ref> Black Hawk welcomed the information, though he would later criticize Neapope for misleading him. He spent the winter in an unsuccessful attempt to recruit additional allies from other tribes and from Keokuk's followers.<ref>Jung, 69; Hall, 116.</ref>\n\nAccording to Neapope's erroneous report, [[Wabokieshiek]] (\"White Cloud\"), a shaman known to Americans as the \"Winnebago Prophet\", had claimed that other tribes were ready to support Black Hawk.<ref name=\"Jung, 66\"/> Wabokieshiek's mother was a [[Ho-Chunk]] (Winnebago), but his father had belonged to a Sauk clan that provided the tribe's civil leaders. When Wabokieshiek joined the British Band in 1832, he would become the ranking Sauk civil chief in the group.<ref>Jung, 74.</ref> His village, [[Prophetstown, Illinois|Prophetstown]], was about thirty-five miles up the Rock River from Saukenuk.<ref>Trask, 63, 69.</ref> The village was inhabited by about 200<ref name=\"Jung, 56\"/> Ho-Chunks, Sauks, Meskwakis, Kickapoos, and Potawatomis who were dissatisfied with tribal leaders who refused to stand up to American expansion.<ref>Dowd, 193; Hall, 110.</ref> Although some Americans would later characterize Wabokieshiek as a primary instigator of the Black Hawk War, the Winnebago Prophet, according to historian John Hall, \"actually discouraged his followers from resorting to armed conflict with the whites\".<ref>Hall, 110.</ref>\n\nOn April 5, 1832, the British Band entered Illinois once again.<ref>Jung, 74; Hall, 116; Trask, 145, gives a more general date of \"probably April 6\".</ref> Numbering about 500 warriors and 600 non-combatants, they crossed near the mouth of the [[Iowa River]] over to Yellow Banks (present-day [[Oquawka, Illinois]]), and then headed north.<ref>Jung, 74\u201375; Trask, 145.</ref> Black Hawk's intentions upon reentering Illinois are not entirely clear, since reports from both white and Indian sources are conflicting. Some said that the British Band intended to reoccupy Saukenuk, while others said that the destination was Prophetstown.<ref>Trask, 149\u201350; Hall, 129\u201330.</ref> According to historian Kerry Trask, \"even Black Hawk may not have been sure where they were going and what they intended to do\".<ref>Trask, 150.</ref>\n\nAs the British Band moved into Illinois, American officials urged Wabokieshiek to advise Black Hawk to turn back. Previously, the Winnebago Prophet had encouraged Black Hawk to come to Prophetstown, arguing that the 1831 agreement made with General Gaines prohibited a return to Saukenuk, but did not  forbid the Sauks from moving to Prophetstown.<ref>Jung, 73; Trask, 146\u201347.</ref> Now, instead of telling Black Hawk to turn back, Wabokieshiek told him that, as long as the British Band remained peaceful, the Americans would have no choice but to let them settle at Prophetstown, especially if the British and the area tribes supported the band.<ref>Hall, 110; Jung, 73.</ref> Although the British Band traveled with armed guards as a security precaution, Black Hawk was probably hoping to avoid a war when he reentered Illinois. The presence of women, children, and the elderly indicated that the band was not a war party.<ref>Eby, 35; Jung, 74\u201375.</ref>\n\n==Intertribal war and American policy==\nAlthough the return of Black Hawk's band worried U.S. officials, they were at the time more concerned about the possibility of a war among the Native American tribes in the region.<ref>Jung 50, 70; Hall, 99\u2013100.</ref> Most accounts of the Black Hawk War focus on the conflict between Black Hawk and the United States, but historian John Hall argues that this overlooks the perspective of many Native American participants. According to Hall, \"the Black Hawk War also involved an intertribal conflict that had smoldered for decades\".<ref>Hall, 9.</ref> Tribes along the Upper Mississippi had long fought for control of diminishing hunting grounds, and the Black Hawk War provided an opportunity for some Natives to resume a war that had nothing to do with Black Hawk.<ref>Hall, 100.</ref>\n\nAfter having displaced the British as the dominant outside power following the War of 1812, the United States had assumed the role of mediator in intertribal disputes. Before the Black Hawk War, U.S. policy discouraged intertribal warfare. This was not strictly for humanitarian reasons: intertribal warfare made it more difficult for the United States to acquire Indian land and move the tribes to the West, a policy known as [[Indian removal]], which had become the primary goal by the late 1820s.<ref>Hall, 55, 95; Buckley, 165.</ref> U.S. efforts at mediation included multi-tribal treaty councils at [[Prairie du Chien]] in [[First Treaty of Prairie du Chien|1825]] and [[Fourth Treaty of Prairie du Chien|1830]], in which tribal boundaries were drawn.<ref>Buckley, 172\u201375; Hall, 77\u201378, 100\u201302.</ref> Native Americans sometimes resented American mediation, especially young men, for whom warfare was an important avenue of social advancement.<ref>Hall, 9, 24, 55, 237.</ref>\n\n[[File:Fort armstrong.JPG|thumb|left|[[Fort Armstrong, Illinois|Fort Armstrong]] was located on Rock Island, which is now known as [[Rock Island Arsenal|Arsenal Island]]. The view is from the Illinois side, with Iowa in the background.]]\n\nThe situation was complicated by the American [[spoils system]]. After [[Andrew Jackson]] assumed the [[President of the United States|U.S. presidency]] in March 1829, many competent [[Indian agent]]s were replaced by unqualified Jackson loyalists, argues historian John Hall. Men like [[Thomas Forsyth (Indian agent)|Thomas Forsyth]], [[John Marsh (pioneer)|John Marsh]], and [[Thomas McKenney]] were replaced by less qualified men such as [[Felix St. Vrain]]. In the 19th century, historian [[Lyman Draper]] argued that the Black Hawk War could have been avoided had Forsyth remained as the agent to the Sauks.<ref>Hall, 103\u201304. Eby, 79, echoed the argument.</ref>\n\nIn 1830, violence threatened to undo American attempts at preventing intertribal warfare. In May, Dakotas ([[Santee Sioux]]) and [[Menominee]]s killed fifteen Meskwakis attending a treaty conference at Prairie du Chien. In retaliation, a party of Meskwakis and Sauks killed twenty-six Menominees, including women and children, at Prairie du Chien in July 1831.<ref>Jung, 49; Hall, 111.</ref> American officials discouraged the Menominees from seeking revenge, but the western bands of the tribe formed a coalition with the Dakotas to strike at the Sauks and Meskwakis.<ref>Hall, 113\u201315.</ref>\n\nHoping to prevent the outbreak of a wider war, American officials ordered the U.S. Army to arrest the Meskwakis who massacred the Menominees.<ref>Hall, 115; Jung, 49\u201350.</ref> General Gaines was ill, and so his subordinate, Brigadier General [[Henry Atkinson (soldier)|Henry Atkinson]], received the assignment.<ref>Hall, 115; Jung, 70.</ref> Atkinson was a middle-aged officer who had ably handled administrative and diplomatic tasks, most notably during the 1827 [[Winnebago War]], but he had never seen combat.<ref>Hall, 115; Jung, 71\u201372; Trask, 143.</ref> On April 8, he set out from [[Jefferson Barracks]] in Missouri, moving up the Mississippi River by steamboat with about 220 soldiers. By chance, Black Hawk and his British Band had just crossed into Illinois. Although Atkinson did not realize it, his boats passed Black Hawk's band.<ref>Trask, 146.</ref>\n\nWhen Atkinson arrived at [[Fort Armstrong, Illinois|Fort Armstrong]] on [[Rock Island Arsenal|Rock Island]] on April 12, he learned that the British Band was in Illinois, and that most of the Meskwakis he wanted to arrest were now with the band.<ref>Hall, 117; Jung, 75.</ref> Like other American officials, Atkinson was convinced that the British Band intended to start a war. Because he had few troops at his disposal, Atkinson hoped to get support from the Illinois state militia. He wrote to Governor Reynolds on April 13, describing\u2014and perhaps purposely exaggerating\u2014the threat that the British Band posed.<ref>Jung, 76; Trask, 158\u201359.</ref> Reynolds, who was eager for a war to drive the Indians out of the state, responded as Atkinson had hoped: he called for militia volunteers to assemble at [[Beardstown, Illinois|Beardstown]] by April 22 to begin a thirty-day enlistment. The 2,100 men who volunteered were organized into a brigade of five regiments under Brigadier General [[Samuel Whiteside]].<ref>Jung, 79\u201380; Trask, 174.</ref> Among the militiamen was [[Abraham Lincoln in the Black Hawk War|23-year-old Abraham Lincoln]], who was elected captain of his company.<ref>Jung, 79.</ref>\n\n==Initial diplomacy==\n[[File:Shabbona (chief)1.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Potawatomi]] chief [[Shabbona]] tried to keep his tribe out of the war.]]\n\nAfter Atkinson's arrival at Rock Island on April 12, 1832, he, Keokuk, and Meskwaki chief [[Wapello (chief)|Wapello]] sent emissaries to the British Band, which was now ascending the Rock River. Black Hawk rejected the messages advising him to turn back.<ref>Jung, 76\u201377; Nichols, 117\u201318.</ref> Colonel [[Zachary Taylor]], a regular army officer who served under Atkinson, later stated that Atkinson should have made an attempt to stop the British Band by force. Some historians have agreed, arguing that Atkinson could have prevented the outbreak of war with more decisive action or astute diplomacy. Cecil Eby charged that \"Atkinson was a paper general, unwilling to proceed until all risk had been eliminated\".<ref>Eby, 93.</ref> Kerry Trask, however, argued that Atkinson was correct in believing that he did not yet have enough troops to stop the British Band.<ref>Trask, 152\u201355.</ref> According to Patrick Jung, leaders on both sides had little chance of avoiding bloodshed at this point, because the militiamen and some of Black Hawk's warriors were spoiling for a fight.<ref>Jung, 86.</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Black Hawk learned that the [[Ho-Chunk]] and [[Potawatomi]] tribes were less supportive than anticipated. As in other tribes, different bands of these tribes often pursued different policies.<ref>Hall, 10\u201311.</ref> The Ho-Chunks who lived along the Rock River in Illinois had family ties to the Sauks; they cautiously supported the British Band while trying not to provoke the Americans.<ref>Hall, 131.</ref> Ho-Chunks in Wisconsin were more divided. Some bands, remembering their loss to the Americans in the 1827 [[Winnebago War]], decided to stay clear of the conflict. Other Ho-Chunks with ties to the Dakotas and Menominees, most notably [[Waukon Decorah]] and his brothers, were eager to fight against the British Band.<ref>Hall, 122\u201323; Jung, 78\u201379.</ref>\n\nMost Potawatomis wanted to remain neutral in the conflict, but found it difficult to do so.<ref>Hall, 125.</ref> Many white settlers, recalling the [[Fort Dearborn massacre]] of 1812, distrusted the Potawatomis and assumed that they would join Black Hawk's uprising.<ref>Hall, 122.</ref> Potawatomi leaders worried that the tribe as a whole would be punished if any Potawatomis supported Black Hawk. At a council outside Chicago on May 1, 1832, Potawatomi leaders including [[Billy Caldwell]] \"passed a resolution declaring any Potawatomi who supported Black Hawk a traitor to his tribe\".<ref>Hall, 132.</ref> In mid May, Potawatomi chiefs [[Shabonna]] and [[Waubonsie]] told Black Hawk that neither they nor the British would come to his aid.<ref>Jung, 86\u201387; Edmunds, 236.</ref>\n\nWithout British supplies, adequate provisions, or Native allies, Black Hawk realized that his band was in serious trouble.<ref>Jung, 83\u201384; Nichols, 120; Trask, 180\u201381.</ref> By some accounts, he was ready to negotiate with Atkinson to end the crisis, but an ill-fated encounter with Illinois militiamen would end all possibility of a peaceful resolution.<ref>Hall, 133.</ref>\n\n==Stillman's Run==\n{{main|Battle of Stillman's Run}}\n[[File:Major Isaiah Stillman.jpg|thumb|left|upright|[[Isaiah Stillman]], militia commander at the [[Battle of Stillman's Run]]]]\n\nGeneral [[Samuel Whiteside]]'s militia brigade had been mustered into federal service at Rock Island under General Atkinson in late April, and divided into a scout or spy battalion commanded by [[James D. Henry]], as well as four regiments (commanded by Colonels John DeWitt, Jacob Fry, John Thomas and Samuel M. Thompson),<ref>Harrington, George B. Past and Present of [[Bureau County, Illinois]]. Chicago, IL, USA: Pioneer Publishing (1906) p. 39 </ref> with judge William Thomas as their quartermaster. Atkinson had allowed Reynolds, Whiteside, and the militiamen to leave up the Rock River on April 27, while he brought up the rear with the regular soldiers, directing his least trained and disciplined men\u2014to \"move upon the Indians should they be within striking distance without waiting for my arrival\".<ref name=\"Jung, 84\">Jung, 84.</ref><ref>[[Thomas Ford (politician)|Thomas Ford]], A History of Illinois: from its commencement as a state in 1818 to 1847 (annotated and introduced by Rodney O Davis; University of Illinois Press 1995) pp. 76-77</ref> Governor Reynolds accompanied the expedition as a major general of militia. \n\nOn May 10 the militia marching up the Rock River in pursuit of the British Band reached Prophetstown (about 35 miles from their starting point at the confluence). Rather than wait per Atkinson's plan, they burned White Cloud's empty village before proceeding about 40 miles upriver to Dixon's Ferry, where they waited for Atkinson and his troops.<ref>Prophetstown State Park brochure, available at https://www.dnr.illinois.gov/publications/Documents/00000097.pdf</ref><ref>Ford p. 78</ref> Although Reynolds wanted to allow the 260 eager militiamen not yet federalized to continue further as scouts, the cautious Whiteside insisted on waiting for Atkinson at the settlement.<ref>Jung, 85\u201386.</ref> Dixon's Ferry had actually been established in 1826 by Ogee, of half-native ancestry, where the wagon trail connecting Peoria to the lead mines in Galena crossed the Rock River; settlers has established cabins along the Peoria/Galena trace and at the crossing, so that by 1829 its post office served settlers up the river as far as Rockford.<ref>William V. Pooley, Settlement of Illinois, 1830-1850 (Thesis submitted to the University of Wisconsin in 1905; printed at Ann Arbor, Michigan, University Microfilms in 1968) p. 147</ref>\n\nOn May 12, learning that Black Hawk's band was only twenty-five miles away, eager militiamen led by Major [[Isaiah Stillman]] left Whiteside's encampment, making another camp on a tributary of the Rock River later named  [[Stillman Valley, Illinois|Stillman Valley]] after him. Seeing a small party of natives with a red flag, Major Samuel Hackelton and some men pursued without waiting for orders, and Hackelton killed a native before returning to Whiteside's camp with the news.<ref>Ford p. 78</ref> However, Black Hawk and others were nearby, and near dusk on May 14 attacked Stillman's party in what became known as the [[Battle of Stillman's Run]]. Accounts of the battle vary.<ref>Jung, 88; Trask, 183.</ref> Black Hawk later stated that he sent three men under a white flag to parley, but the Americans imprisoned them and opened fire on a second group of emissaries who followed. Some militiamen claimed they never saw a white flag; others believed that the flag was a ruse the Indians used to set an ambush.<ref>Jung, 88\u201389; Trask, 186.</ref> All accounts agree that Black Hawk's warriors attacked the militia camp at dusk, that the much more numerous militia were routed, and stragglers reached Whiteside's camp. To Black Hawk's surprise, his forty warriors killed twelve Illinois militiamen; his British Band suffered only three fatalities.<ref>Jung, 89; Hall, 133\u201334.</ref>\n\nThe Battle of Stillman's Run proved a turning point. Before the battle, Black Hawk had not committed to war. Now he determined to avenge what he saw as the treacherous killing of his warriors under a flag of truce.<ref>Jung, 89.</ref> Whiteside too was incensed when he returned to the battle site with a burial party and viewed the mutilated corpses. <ref>\"Battle of Stillman's Run\" in William B. Kessell, Encyclopedia of Native American Wars and Warfare (2005), available online</ref>  After Stillman's defeat, American leaders like President Jackson and [[United States Secretary of War|Secretary of War]] [[Lewis Cass]] refused to consider a diplomatic solution; they wanted a resounding victory over Black Hawk to serve as an example to other Native Americans who might consider similar uprisings.<ref>Jung, 118\u201320.</ref>\n\n==Initial raids==\n{| style=\"text-align:center; float:right; clear:right\"\n|-\n| {{Black Hawk War Map}}\n|-\n|Map of Black Hawk War sites<br />[[File:Red Battle X.png|8px|link=]] <small>Battle (with name)</small> [[File:Red pog.svg|7px|link=]] <small>Fort / settlement</small> [[File:Green pog.svg|7px|link=]] <small>Native village</small><br /><small>Symbols are wikilinked to article</small>\n|}\n\nWith hostilities now underway, and few allies to depend upon, Black Hawk sought a place of refuge for the women, children, and elderly in his band. Accepting an offer from the Rock River Ho-Chunks, the band traveled further upriver to [[Lake Koshkonong]] in the [[Michigan Territory]] and camped in an isolated place known as the \"Island\".<ref>Jung, 93\u201394.</ref> With the non-combatants secure, members of the British Band, with a number of Ho-Chunk and Potawatomi allies, began raiding white settlers.<ref>Jung, 94, 108.</ref> Not all Native Americans in the region supported this turn of events; most notably, Potawatomi chief [[Shabonna]] rode throughout the settlements, warning whites of the impending attacks.<ref>Edmunds, 237; Trask, 200; Jung, 95.</ref>\n\nThe initial raiding parties consisted primarily of Ho-Chunk and Potawatomi warriors. The first attack came on May 19, 1832, when Ho-Chunks [[Buffalo Grove ambush|ambushed six men]] near [[Buffalo Grove, Illinois (Ogle County)|Buffalo Grove, Illinois]], killing a man named William Durley.<ref>Jung, 95; Trask, 198.</ref> Durley's [[scalping|scalped]] and mutilated body was found by Indian agent [[Felix St. Vrain]]. The Indian agent was himself [[St. Vrain massacre|killed and mutilated]], along with three other men, several days later at [[Kellogg's Grove]].<ref>Jung, 97; Trask, 198\u201399.</ref>\n\nThe Ho-Chunks and Potawatomis who took part in the war were sometimes motivated by grievances not directly related to Black Hawk's objectives.<ref name=\"Jung, 95\">Jung, 95.</ref> One such incident was the [[Indian Creek massacre]]. In the spring of 1832, Potawatomis living along Indian Creek were upset that a settler named William Davis had dammed the creek, preventing fish from reaching their village. Davis ignored the protests, and assaulted a Potawatomi man who tried to dismantle the dam.<ref>Hall, 135\u201336.</ref> The Black Hawk War provided the Indian Creek Potawatomis with an opportunity for revenge. On May 21, about fifty Potawatomis and three Sauks from the British Band attacked Davis's settlement, killing, scalping, and mutilating fifteen men, women, and children.<ref>Jung, 95; Trask, 202.</ref> Two teenage girls from the settlement were kidnapped and taken to Black Hawk's camp.<ref>Jung, 96; Trask, 215.</ref> A Ho-Chunk chief named White Crow negotiated their release two weeks later.<ref>Trask, 212\u201317.</ref> Like other Rock River Ho-Chunks, White Crow was trying to placate the Americans while clandestinely aiding the British Band.<ref>Hall, 152\u201354; 164\u201365.</ref>\n\n==American reorganization==\nNews of Stillman's defeat, the Indian Creek massacre, and other smaller attacks triggered panic among the white population. Many settlers fled to [[Chicago]], then a small town, which became overcrowded with hungry refugees.<ref>Trask, 200\u201306; Jung, 97.</ref> Many Potawatomis also fled towards Chicago, not wanting to get caught in the conflict nor be mistaken for hostiles.<ref>Edmunds, 238; Jung, 103.</ref> Throughout the region, settlers hurriedly organized militia units and built small forts.<ref>Jung, 96.</ref>\n\nAfter Stillman's defeat on May 14, the regulars and militia continued up the Rock River to search for Black Hawk. The militiamen became discouraged at not being able to find the British Band. When they heard about the Indian raids, many deserted so that they could return home to defend their families.<ref>Trask, 194\u201396.</ref> As morale plummeted, Governor Reynolds asked his militia officers to vote on whether to continue the campaign. General Whiteside, disgusted with the performance of his men, cast the tie-breaking vote in favor of disbanding.<ref>Jung, 100; Trask, 196.</ref> Most of Whiteside's brigade disbanded at [[Ottawa, Illinois]], on May 28. About 300 men, including Abraham Lincoln, agreed to remain in the field for twenty more days until a new militia force could be organized.<ref>Jung, 101; Trask, 196\u201397.</ref>\n\nAs Whiteside's brigade disbanded, Atkinson organized a new force in June 1832 that he dubbed the \"Army of the Frontier\".<ref>Jung, 115.</ref> The army consisted of 629 regular army infantrymen and 3,196 mounted militia volunteers. The militia was divided into three brigades commanded by Brigadier Generals [[Alexander Posey (general)|Alexander Posey]], [[Milton Alexander]], and [[James D. Henry]]. Since many men were assigned to local patrols and guard duties, Atkinson had only 450 regulars and 2,100 militiamen available for campaigning.<ref>Jung, 114\u201315.</ref> Many more militiamen served in units that were not part of the Army of the Frontier's three brigades. Abraham Lincoln, for example, reenlisted as a private in an independent company that was taken into federal service. [[Henry Dodge]], a Michigan territorial militia colonel who would prove to be one of the best commanders in the war,<ref>Jung, 103.</ref> fielded a battalion of mounted volunteers that numbered 250 men at its strongest. The overall number of militiamen who took part in the war is not precisely known; the total from Illinois alone has been estimated at six to seven thousand.<ref>Jung, 116.</ref>\n\nIn addition to organizing a new militia army, Atkinson also began to recruit Native American allies, reversing the previous American policy of trying to prevent intertribal warfare.<ref>Hall, 143\u201345.</ref> Menominees, Dakotas, and some Ho-Chunks bands were eager to go to war against the British Band. By June 6, agent [[Joseph M. Street]] had assembled about 225 Natives at Prairie du Chien.<ref>Hall, 148.</ref> This force included about eighty Dakotas under [[Wapasha II|Wabasha]] and L'Arc, forty Menominees, and several bands of Ho Chunks.<ref>Hall, 148; Jung 104.</ref> Although the Indian warriors followed their own leaders, Atkinson placed the force under the nominal command of [[William S. Hamilton]], a militia colonel and a son of [[Alexander Hamilton]]. Hamilton would prove to be an unfortunate choice to lead the force; historian John Hall characterized him as \"pretentious and unqualified\".<ref>Hall, 145.</ref> Before long, the Indians became frustrated with marching around under Hamilton and not seeing any action. Some Menominee scouts remained, but most of the Natives eventually left Hamilton and fought the war on their own terms.<ref>Hall, 162\u201363; Jung, 105.</ref>\n\n==June raids==\nIn June 1832, after hearing that Atkinson was forming a new army, Black Hawk began sending out raiding parties. Perhaps hoping to lead the Americans away from his camp at Lake Koshkonong, he targeted areas to the west.<ref>Jung, 108.</ref> The first major attack occurred on June 14 near present-day [[South Wayne, Wisconsin]], when a band of about 30 warriors attacked a group of farmers, [[Spafford Farm massacre|killing and scalping four]].<ref>Jung, 109.</ref>\n\n[[File:Pecatonica Battleground1.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Painting of rolling hills, a river, and trees|An 1857 painting of the battlefield at Horseshoe Bend]]\n\nResponding to this attack, militia Colonel Henry Dodge gathered a force of twenty-nine mounted volunteers and set out in pursuit of the attackers. On June 16, Dodge and his men cornered about eleven of the raiders at a bend in the [[Pecatonica River]]. In a brief battle, the Americans killed and scalped all of the Natives.<ref>Jung, 109\u201310; Trask, 233\u201334.</ref> The [[Battle of Horseshoe Bend (1832)|Battle of Horseshoe Bend]] (or Battle of Pecatonica) was the first real American victory in the war, and helped restore public confidence in the volunteer militia force.<ref>Jung, 110; Trask, 234\u201337.</ref>\n\nOn the same day of Dodge's victory, another skirmish took place at [[Kellogg's Grove]] in present-day [[Stephenson County, Illinois]]. American forces had occupied Kellogg's Grove in an effort to intercept war parties raiding to the west. In the [[First Battle of Kellogg's Grove]], militia commanded by [[Adam W. Snyder]] pursued a British Band raiding party of about thirty warriors. Three Illinois militiamen and six Native warriors died in the fighting.<ref>Jung, 111\u201312.</ref> Two days later, on June 18, militia under [[James W. Stephenson]] encountered what was probably the same war party near [[Yellow Creek (Illinois)|Yellow Creek]]. The [[Battle of Waddams Grove]] became a hard fought, hand-to-hand melee. Three militiamen and five or six Indians were killed in the action.<ref>Jung, 112; Trask, 220\u201321.</ref>\n\nBack on June 6, when a civilian miner was killed by raiders near the village of [[Blue Mounds, Wisconsin|Blue Mounds]] in the Michigan Territory, residents began to fear that the Rock River Ho-Chunks were joining the war.<ref>Trask, 220.</ref> On June 20, a Ho-Chunk raiding party estimated by one eyewitness to be as large as 100 warriors [[Attacks at Fort Blue Mounds|attacked the settler fort]] at Blue Mounds. Two militiamen were killed in the attack, one of whom was badly mutilated.<ref>Jung, 112; Trask, 220.</ref>\n\n[[File:Elizabeth Il Apple River Fort2.JPG|thumb|right|alt=A wooden stockade fronted by a wall of vertically-placed logs and a corner blockhouse|Replica of Apple River Fort in Elizabeth, Illinois]]\n\nOn June 24, 1832, Black Hawk and about 200 warriors attacked at the hastily constructed [[Apple River Fort]], near present-day [[Elizabeth, Illinois]]. Local settlers, warned of Black Hawk's approach, took refuge in the fort, which was defended by about 20<ref name=\"Trask, 222\">Trask, 222.</ref> to 35<ref>Jung, 113.</ref> militiamen. The [[Battle of Apple River Fort]] lasted about forty-five minutes. The women and girls inside the fort, under the direction of [[Elizabeth Armstrong (settler)|Elizabeth Armstrong]], loaded muskets and molded bullets.<ref name=\"Trask, 222\"/> After losing several men, Black Hawk broke off the siege, looted the nearby homes, and headed back towards his camp.<ref>Jung, 114.</ref>\n\nThe next day, June 25, Black Hawk's party encountered a militia battalion commanded by Major [[John Dement]]. In the [[Second Battle of Kellogg's Grove]], Black Hawk's warriors drove the militiamen inside their fort and commenced a two-hour siege. After losing nine warriors and killing five militiamen, Black Hawk broke off the siege and returned to his main camp at Lake Koshkonong.<ref>Jung, 121\u201323.</ref> This would prove to be Black Hawk's last military success in the war. With his band running low on food, he decided to take them back across the Mississippi.<ref>Jung, 124.</ref>\n\n==Final campaign==\nOn June 15, 1832, President [[Andrew Jackson]], displeased with Atkinson's handling of the war, appointed General [[Winfield Scott]] to take command.<ref>Jung, 118; Trask, 272.</ref> Scott gathered about 950 troops from eastern army posts just as a [[Second cholera pandemic|cholera pandemic]] had spread to eastern North America.<ref>Jung, 139.</ref> As Scott's troops traveled by steamboat from [[Buffalo, New York]], across the Great Lakes towards Chicago, his men started getting sick from cholera, with many of them dying. At each place the vessels landed, the sick were deposited and soldiers deserted. By the time the last steamboat landed in Chicago, Scott had only about 350 effective soldiers left.<ref>Jung, 140\u201341; Trask, 271\u201375.</ref> On July 29, Scott began a hurried journey west, ahead of his troops, eager to take command of what was certain to be the war's final campaign, but he would be too late to see any combat.<ref>Jung, 141; Trask, 276.</ref>\n\nGeneral Atkinson, who learned in early July that Scott would be taking command, hoped to bring the war to a successful conclusion before Scott's arrival.<ref>Jung, 130.</ref> The Americans had difficulty locating the British Band, however, thanks in part to false intelligence given to them by area Native Americans. Potawatomis and Ho-Chunks in Illinois, many of whom had sought to remain neutral in the war, decided to cooperate with the Americans. Tribal leaders knew that some of their warriors had aided the British Band, and so they hoped that a highly visible show of support for the Americans would dissuade U.S. officials from punishing the tribes after the conflict was over. Wearing white headbands to distinguish themselves from hostile Natives, Ho-Chunks and Potawatomis served as guides for Atkinson's army.<ref>Edmunds, 239; Hall, 244\u201349.</ref> Ho-Chunks sympathetic to the plight of Black Hawk's people misled Atkinson into thinking that the British Band was still at Lake Koshkonong. While Atkinson's men were trudging through the swamps and running low on provisions, the British Band had in fact relocated miles to the north.<ref>Jung, 131\u201334.</ref> Potawatomis under Billy Caldwell also managed to demonstrate support for the Americans while avoiding battle.<ref>Hall, 165\u201367.</ref>\n\nIn mid-July, Colonel Dodge learned from m\u00e9tis trader Pierre Paquette that the British Band was camped near the Rock River rapids, at present [[Hustisford, Wisconsin]].<ref>Jung, 142.</ref> Dodge and [[James D. Henry]] set out in pursuit from [[Fort Winnebago]] on July 15.<ref>Jung, 144.</ref> The British Band, reduced to fewer than 600 people due to death and desertion, headed for the Mississippi River as the militia approached.<ref>Jung, 146\u201348.</ref> The Americans pursued them, killing and scalping several Native stragglers along the way.<ref>Jung, 149\u201350.</ref>\n\n===Wisconsin Heights===\n{{Main|Battle of Wisconsin Heights}}\n\nOn July 21, 1832, the militiamen caught up with the British Band near present-day [[Sauk City, Wisconsin]]. To buy time for the noncombatants to cross the Wisconsin River, Black Hawk and Neapope confronted the Americans in a rear guard action that became known as the [[Battle of Wisconsin Heights]]. Black Hawk was desperately outnumbered, leading about 50 Sauks and 60 to 70 Kickapoos against 750 militiamen.<ref>Jung, 153\u201356.</ref> The battle was a lopsided victory for the militiamen, who lost only one man while killing as many as 68 of Black Hawk's warriors.<ref>Jung, 156; Trask, 260\u201361.</ref> Despite the high casualties, the battle allowed much of the British Band, including many women and children, to escape across the river.<ref name=\"lewis\">{{cite web|url=http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/page2c.html |title=The Black Hawk War of 1832 |last=Lewis |first=James |work=Abraham Lincoln Digitization Project |publisher=Northern Illinois University |page=2c |accessdate=2009-08-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090815021319/http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/page2c.html |archivedate=2009-08-15 }}</ref> Black Hawk had managed to hold off a much larger force while allowing most of his people to escape, a difficult military operation that impressed some U.S. Army officers when they learned of it.<ref>Jung, 157.</ref>\n\nThe Battle of Wisconsin Heights had been a victory for the militia; no regular soldiers of the U.S. Army had been present.<ref>Jung, 156.</ref> Atkinson and the regulars joined up with the volunteers several days after the battle. With a force of about 400 regulars and 900 militiamen, the Americans crossed the Wisconsin River on July 27 and resumed the pursuit of the British Band.<ref>Jung, 161; Trask, 268.</ref> The British Band was moving slow, encumbered with wounded warriors and people dying of starvation. The Americans followed the trail of dead bodies, cast off equipment, and the remains of horses the hungry Natives had eaten.<ref>Jung, 162; Trask, 270\u201371.</ref>\n\n===Bad Axe===\n{{Main|Battle of Bad Axe}}\n\nAfter the Battle of Wisconsin Heights, a messenger from Black Hawk had shouted to the militiamen that the starving British Band was going back across the Mississippi and would fight no more. No one in the American camp understood the message, however, since their Ho-Chunk guides were not present to interpret.<ref>Nichols, 131; Trask, 266.</ref> Black Hawk may have believed that the Americans had gotten the message, and that they had not pursued him after the Battle of Wisconsin Heights. He apparently expected that the Americans were going to let his band recross the Mississippi unmolested.<ref>Jung, 168\u201369.</ref>\n\n[[File: Battle of Bad Axe.jpg|300px|thumb|right|Native American women and children fleeing for their lives, preparing to cross the Mississippi River, during Black Hawk's defeat at the [[Battle of Bad Axe]]]]\n\nThe Americans, however, had no intentions of letting the British Band escape. The [[Warrior (steamboat)|''Warrior'']], a steamboat outfitted with an artillery piece, patrolled the Mississippi River, while American-allied Dakotas, Menominees, and Ho-Chunks watched the banks.<ref>Hall, 192\u201394.</ref> On August 1, the ''Warrior'' arrived at the mouth of the [[Bad Axe River]], where the Dakotas told the Americans that they would find Black Hawk's people.<ref>Jung, 164\u201365; Hall, 194.</ref> Black Hawk raised a white flag in an attempt to surrender, but his intentions may have been garbled in translation.<ref>Jung, 165; Nichols, 133.</ref> The Americans, in no mood to accept a surrender anyway, thought that the Indians were using the white flag to set an ambush. When they became certain that the Natives on land were the British Band, they opened fire. Twenty-three Natives were killed in the exchange of gunfire, while just one soldier on the ''Warrior'' was injured.<ref>Jung, 166; Trask, 279.</ref>\n\n[[File:1832 Battle of Bad Axe and steamboat Warrior.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The steamboat ''[[Warrior (steamboat)|Warrior]]'' firing upon escaping Native Americans trying to get across the Mississippi River to safety in Iowa]]\n\nAfter the ''Warrior'' left, Black Hawk decided to seek refuge in the north with the [[Ojibwe]]s. Only about 50 people, including Wabokieshiek, agreed to go with him; the others remained, determined to cross the Mississippi and return to Sauk territory.<ref>Jung, 166; Nichols, 133. Jung says \"about 60 people\" left with Black Hawk; Nichols, 135, estimated \"perhaps forty\".</ref> The next morning, on August 2, Black Hawk was heading north when he learned that the American army had closed in on the members of the British Band who were trying to cross the Mississippi.<ref name=\"Jung, 169\">Jung, 169.</ref> He tried to rejoin the main body, but after a skirmish with American troops near present-day [[Victory, Wisconsin]], he gave up the attempt.<ref name=\"Jung, 169\"/> Sauk chief [[Weesheet]] later criticized Black Hawk and Wabokieshiek for abandoning the people during the final battle of the war.<ref>Jung, 180\u201381; Trask, 282.</ref>\n\nThe [[Battle of Bad Axe]] began at about 9:00 am on August 2 after the Americans caught up with the remnants of the British Band a few miles downstream from the mouth of the Bad Axe River. The British Band was reduced to roughly 500 people by this time, including about 150 warriors.<ref>Jung, 170.</ref> The warriors fought with the Americans while the Native noncombatants frantically tried to cross the river. Many made it to one of the two nearby islands, but were dislodged after the steamboat ''Warrior'' returned at noon, carrying regulars and Menominees allied with the Americans.<ref>Trask, 286\u201387; Jung, 170\u201371.</ref>\n\nThe battle was another lopsided victory for the Americans, who lost just 14 men, including one Menominee who died by [[friendly fire]] and was buried with honors alongside the white soldiers.<ref>Jung, 171\u201372; Hall, 196.</ref> At least 260 members of the British Band were killed, including about 110 who drowned while trying to cross the river. Although the regular soldiers of the U.S. Army generally tried to avoid needless bloodshed, many of the militiamen intentionally killed Native noncombatants, sometimes in cold blood.<ref>Trask, 285\u201386, 293.</ref> The encounter was, in the words of historian Patrick Jung, \"less of a battle and more of a massacre\".<ref name=\"Jung, 172\"/>\n\nMenominees from [[Green Bay, Wisconsin|Green Bay]], who had mobilized a battalion of nearly 300 men, arrived too late for the battle. They were upset at having missed the chance to fight their old enemies, and so on August 10, General Scott sent 100 of them after a part of the British Band that had escaped.<ref>Hall, 197.</ref> Indian agent Samuel C. Stambaugh, who accompanied them, urged the Menominees not to take any scalps, but Chief Grizzly Bear insisted that such a prohibition could not be enforced.<ref>Hall, 198.</ref> The group tracked down about ten Sauks, only two of whom were warriors. The Menominees killed and scalped the warriors, but spared the women and children.<ref>Hall, 199.</ref>\n\nThe Dakotas, who had volunteered 150 warriors to fight against the Sauks and Meskwakis, also arrived too late to participate in the Battle of Bad Axe, but they pursued the members of the British Band who made it across the Mississippi into Iowa. On about August 9, in the final engagement of the war,<ref>Hall, 202.</ref> they attacked the remnants of the British Band along the [[Cedar River (Iowa River)|Cedar River]], killing 68 and taking 22 prisoners.<ref>Jung, 175; Hall, 201.</ref> Ho-Chunks also hunted survivors of the British Band, taking between fifty and sixty scalps.<ref>Jung, 177; Hall, 210\u201311.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThe Black Hawk War resulted in the deaths of 77 white settlers, militiamen, and regular soldiers.<ref name=\"Jung, 172\">Jung, 172.</ref> This figure does not include the deaths from cholera suffered by the relief force under General Winfield Scott. Estimates of how many members of the British Band died during the conflict range from about 450 to 600, or about half of the 1,100 people who entered Illinois with Black Hawk in 1832.<ref>Jung, 172, 179.</ref>\n\nA number of American men with political ambitions fought in the Black Hawk War. At least seven future [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]]s took part, as did four future Illinois governors; future governors of Michigan, Nebraska, and the [[Wisconsin Territory]]; and one future U.S. president.<ref name=\"lewis2d\">{{cite web|url=http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/page2d.html|title=The Black Hawk War of 1832|last=Lewis|first=James|work=Abraham Lincoln Historical Digitization Project|publisher=Northern Illinois University|page=2d|accessdate=2009-08-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090619071514/http://lincoln.lib.niu.edu/blackhawk/page2d.html|archivedate=2009-06-19}}</ref> The Black Hawk War demonstrated to American officials the need for mounted troops to fight a mounted foe. During the war, the U.S. Army did not have cavalry; the only mounted soldiers were part-time volunteers. After the war, Congress created the [[US Army Rangers#Black Hawk War|Mounted Ranger Battalion]] under the command of [[Henry Dodge]], which was expanded to the [[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Cavalry Regiment]] in 1833.<ref>Jung 205\u201306.</ref>\n\n===Black Hawk's imprisonment and legacy===\n[[File:Black hawk statue.jpg|thumb|Statue of Black Hawk, [[Black Hawk State Historic Site]]]]\n\nAfter the Battle of Bad Axe, Black Hawk, Wabokieshiek, and their followers traveled northeast to seek refuge with the Ojibwes. American officials offered a reward of $100 and forty horses for Black Hawk's capture.<ref>Jung, 181.</ref> While camping near present-day [[Tomah, Wisconsin]], Black Hawk's party was seen by a passing Ho-Chunk man, who alerted his village chief. The village council sent a delegation to Black Hawk's camp and convinced him to surrender to the Americans. On August 27, 1832, Black Hawk and Wabokieshiek surrendered at Prairie du Chien to Indian agent Joseph Street.<ref>Jung, 182; Trask, 294\u201395.</ref> Colonel Zachary Taylor took custody of the prisoners, and sent them by steamboat to Jefferson Barracks, escorted by Lieutenants [[Jefferson Davis]] and [[Robert Anderson (Civil War)|Robert Anderson]].<ref>Jung, 183.</ref>\n\nBy war's end, Black Hawk and nineteen other leaders of the British Band were incarcerated at Jefferson Barracks. Most of the prisoners were released in the succeeding months, but in April 1833, Black Hawk, Wabokieshiek, Neapope, and three others were transferred to [[Fort Monroe]] in Virginia, which was better equipped to hold prisoners.<ref>Jung, 190\u201391.</ref> The American public was eager to catch a glimpse of the captured Indians. Large crowds gathered in [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]] and [[Cincinnati]] to watch them pass.<ref>Trask, 298; Jung, 192.</ref> On April 26, the prisoners met briefly with President Jackson in [[Washington, D.C.]], before being taken to Fort Monroe.<ref>Jung, 192; Trask, 298.</ref> Even in prison they were treated as celebrities: they posed for portraits by artists such as [[Charles Bird King]] and [[John Wesley Jarvis]], and a dinner was held in their honor before they left.<ref>Nichols, 147; Trask, 298.</ref>\n\nAmerican officials decided to release the prisoners after a few weeks. First, however, the Natives were required to visit several large U.S. cities on the east coast. This was a tactic often used when Native American leaders came to the East, because it was thought that a demonstration of the size and power of the United States would discourage future resistance to U.S. expansion.<ref>Jung, 191; Nichols, 148; Trask, 300.</ref> Beginning on June 4, 1833, Black Hawk and his companions were taken on a tour of [[Baltimore]], [[Philadelphia]], and [[New York City]]. They attended dinners and plays, and were shown a battleship, various public buildings, and a military parade. Huge crowds gathered to see them. Black Hawk's handsome son Nasheweskaska (Whirling Thunder) was a particular favorite.<ref>Jung, 195\u201397; Nichols, 148\u201349; Trask, 300\u201301.</ref> Reaction in the west, however, was less welcoming. When the prisoners traveled through [[Detroit]] on their way home, one crowd burned and hanged [[effigies]] of the Indians.<ref>Trask, 301\u201302; Jung, 197.</ref>\n\nAccording to historian Kerry Trask, Black Hawk and his fellow prisoners were treated like celebrities because the Indians served as a living embodiment of the [[noble savage]] myth that had become popular in the eastern United States. Then and later, argues Trask, white Americans absolved themselves of complicity in the dispossession of Native Americans by expressing admiration or sympathy for defeated Indians like Black Hawk.<ref>Trask, 298\u2013303.</ref> The mythologizing of Black Hawk continued, argues Trask, with the many plaques and memorials that were later erected in his honor. \"Indeed,\" writes Trask, \"most of the reconstructed memory of the Black Hawk War has been designed to make white people feel good about themselves.\"<ref>Trask, 308.</ref> Black Hawk also became an admired symbol of resistance among Native Americans, even among descendants of those who had opposed him.\n\n===Treaties and removals===\nThe Black Hawk War marked the end of Native armed resistance to U.S. expansion in the [[Northwest Territory|Old Northwest]]<ref>Buckley, 210; Hall, 255; Jung, 208.</ref> The war provided an opportunity for American officials such as Andrew Jackson, Lewis Cass, and John Reynolds to compel Native American tribes to sell their lands east of the Mississippi River and move to the West, a policy known as [[Indian removal]]. Officials conducted a number of treaties after the war to purchase the remaining Native American land claims in the Old Northwest. The Dakotas and Menominees, who won approval from American officials for their role in the war, largely avoided postwar removal pressure until later decades.<ref>Hall, 207.</ref>\n\nAfter the war, American officials learned that some Ho-Chunks had aided Black Hawk more than had been previously known.<ref>Hall, 209\u201310.</ref> Eight Ho-Chunks were briefly imprisoned at Fort Winnebago for their role in the war, but charges against them were eventually dropped due to a lack of witnesses.<ref>Jung, 207.</ref> In September 1832, General Scott and Governor Reynolds conducted a treaty with the Ho-Chunks at Rock Island. The Ho-Chunks ceded all their land south of the Wisconsin River in exchange for a forty-mile strip of land in Iowa and annual payments of $10,000 for twenty-seven years.<ref>Hall, 212\u201313; Jung, 285\u201386.</ref> The land in Iowa was known as the \"Neutral Ground\" because it had been designated in 1830 as a buffer zone between the Dakotas and their enemies to the south, the Sauks and Meskwakis.<ref>Jung, 49; Buckley, 203.</ref> Scott hoped that the settlement of the Ho-Chunks in the Neutral Ground would help keep the peace.<ref name=\"Jung, 186\">Jung, 186.</ref> Ho-Chunks remaining in Wisconsin were pressured to sign a removal treaty in 1837, even though leaders such as Waukon Decorah had been U.S. allies during the Black Hawk War. General Atkinson was assigned to use the army to forcibly relocate those Ho-Chunks who refused to move to Iowa.<ref>Hall, 259\u201361.</ref>\n\nFollowing the September 1832 treaty with the Ho-Chunks, Scott and Reynolds conducted another with the Sauks and Meskwakis, with Keokuk and Wapello serving as the primary representatives of their tribes. Scott told the assembled chiefs that \"if a particular part of a nation goes out of their country, and makes war, the whole nation is responsible\".<ref name=\"Jung, 186\"/> The tribes sold about 6 million acres (24,000&nbsp;km\u00b2) of [[Black Hawk Purchase|land in eastern Iowa]] to the United States for payments of $20,000 per year for thirty years, among other provisions.<ref>Trask, 304; Jung, 187.</ref> Keokuk was granted a [[Indian reservation|reservation]] within the cession and recognized by the Americans as the primary chief of the Sauks and Meskwakis.<ref>Jung, 187.</ref> The tribes sold the reservation to the United States in 1836, and additional land in Iowa the following year.<ref>Jung, 198.</ref> Their last lands in Iowa were sold in 1842, and most of the Natives moved to a reservation in Kansas.<ref>Jung, 201\u201302.</ref>\n\nThanks to the decision of Potawatomi leaders to aid the U.S. during the war, American officials did not seize tribal land as [[war reparations]]. Instead, only three individuals accused of leading the Indian Creek massacre were tried in court; they were acquitted.<ref>Edmunds, 238; Hall, 208, 215.</ref> Nevertheless, the drive to purchase Potawatomi land west of the Mississippi began in October 1832, when [[Treaty of Tippecanoe|commissioners in Indiana]] bought a large amount of Potawatomi land, even though not all Potawatomi bands were represented at the treaty.<ref>Hall, 215\u201316.</ref> The tribe was compelled to sell their remaining land west of the Mississippi in a [[Treaty of Chicago|treaty held in Chicago]] in September 1833.<ref>Edmunds, 247\u201348; Hall, 231.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Black Hawk War}}\n* [[Abraham Lincoln in the Black Hawk War]]\n* [[Second Black Hawk War]]\n* [[American Indian Wars]]\n* [[Sixty Years' War]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==References==\n===Secondary sources===\n* Buckley, Jay H. ''William Clark: Indian Diplomat''. Norman, Oklahoma: University of Oklahoma Press, 2008. {{ISBN|978-0-8061-3911-1}}; {{ISBN|0-8061-3911-0}}.\n* Eby, Cecil. ''\"That Disgraceful Affair\", The Black Hawk War''. New York: Norton, 1973. {{ISBN|0-393-05484-5}}.\n* Edmunds, R. David. ''The Potawatomis: Keepers of the Fire''. University of Oklahoma Press, 1978. {{ISBN|0-8061-1478-9}}\n* Hall, John W. ''Uncommon Defense: Indian Allies in the Black Hawk War''. Harvard University Press, 2009. {{ISBN|0-674-03518-6}}.\n* Jung, Patrick J. ''The Black Hawk War of 1832''. Norman, Oklahoma: University of Oklahoma Press, 2007. {{ISBN|0-8061-3811-4}}.\n* Nichols, Roger L. ''Black Hawk and the Warrior's Path''. Arlington Heights, Illinois: Harlan Davidson, 1992. {{ISBN|0-88295-884-4}}.\n* Nichols, Roger L. ''Warrior Nations: The United States and Indian Peoples.'' Norman, OK: University of Oklahoma Press, 2013.\n* Owens, Robert M. ''Mr. Jefferson's Hammer: William Henry Harrison and the Origins of American Indian Policy''. Norman, Oklahoma: University of Oklahoma Press, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-8061-3842-8}}.\n* Trask, Kerry A. ''Black Hawk: The Battle for the Heart of America''. New York: Henry Holt and Company, 2006. {{ISBN|0-8050-7758-8}}.\n\n===Primary sources===\n* Black Hawk. ''Life of Black Hawk''. Originally published 1833. Reprinted often in various editions. Revised in 1882 with inauthentic embellishments; most modern editions restore the original wording.\n* Whitney, Ellen M., ed. ''The Black Hawk War, 1831\u20131832: Volume I, Illinois Volunteers''. Springfield, Illinois: Illinois State Historical Library, 1970. {{ISBN|0-912154-22-5}}. Published as Volume XXXV of ''Collections of the Illinois State Historical Library''. 